WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:00.680 --> 00:00:04.630
&gt;&gt; From the Library of
Congress in Washington, D.C..

00:00:18.660 --> 00:00:19.990
&gt;&gt; Ladies and Gentlemen.

00:00:19.990 --> 00:00:22.360
A video message from
the fourteenth Librarian

00:00:22.360 --> 00:00:24.610
of Congress, Carla Hayden.

00:00:24.610 --> 00:00:26.030
&gt;&gt; Dr. Carla Hayden: Good
evening, and thank you

00:00:26.030 --> 00:00:28.580
for joining the Library
on this special night.

00:00:28.580 --> 00:00:30.690
Remembering Denis Johnson,

00:00:30.690 --> 00:00:35.290
recipient of the 2017
Prize for American Fiction.

00:00:35.290 --> 00:00:37.630
I'm sorry I can't
be there with you.

00:00:37.630 --> 00:00:40.590
But I know it will be a
memorable conversation

00:00:40.590 --> 00:00:42.360
with these extraordinary
authors.

00:00:42.360 --> 00:00:46.370
The Library of Congress honors
a writer's lifetime achievement.

00:00:46.370 --> 00:00:47.670
The Fiction Prize,

00:00:47.670 --> 00:00:50.660
at the National Book
Festival each year.

00:00:50.660 --> 00:00:53.420
So I didn't want to miss
the opportunity to share

00:00:53.420 --> 00:00:55.970
with you some news
about this year's event.

00:00:55.970 --> 00:00:58.710
On Saturday, September 1.

00:00:58.710 --> 00:01:01.280
Once again, this
celebration of books

00:01:01.280 --> 00:01:03.250
and reading will feature some

00:01:03.250 --> 00:01:06.560
of the biggest names
in every genre.

00:01:06.560 --> 00:01:10.760
In History, I'm thrilled to
announce that former Secretary

00:01:10.760 --> 00:01:13.840
of State, Madeleine
Albright, will join us.

00:01:13.840 --> 00:01:18.180
Also Doris Kearns Goodwin, John
Meacham, and Ron [inaudible].

00:01:18.180 --> 00:01:23.320
Best-selling author Amy Tan
will discuss her new memoir.

00:01:23.320 --> 00:01:25.620
Where the Past Begins.

00:01:25.620 --> 00:01:28.090
Dave Eggers, Jennifer Egan,

00:01:28.090 --> 00:01:31.650
and Isobel Liende
will all be with us.

00:01:31.650 --> 00:01:33.040
And children's author

00:01:33.040 --> 00:01:37.190
and Pulitzer Prize winner
Junot Diaz will join us.

00:01:37.190 --> 00:01:41.890
Our US Poet Laureate Tracy K.
Smith, and National Ambassador

00:01:41.890 --> 00:01:43.280
for Young People's Literature,

00:01:43.280 --> 00:01:45.700
Jacqueline Woodson
will be there too.

00:01:45.700 --> 00:01:48.660
This is just a hint
at the things to come.

00:01:48.660 --> 00:01:51.320
More names will be
announced soon.

00:01:51.320 --> 00:01:53.620
I hope to see you there.

00:01:55.930 --> 00:01:58.430
&gt;&gt; Please welcome the
Director of National

00:01:58.430 --> 00:02:02.510
and International
Outreach, Dr. Jane McAuliffe.

00:02:02.510 --> 00:02:13.050
[ Applause ]

00:02:13.050 --> 00:02:14.350
&gt;&gt; Dr. Jane McAuliffe:
Good evening.

00:02:14.350 --> 00:02:15.930
As you've just heard, I'm
Jane McAuliffe, the Director

00:02:15.930 --> 00:02:20.400
of National and International
Outreach here at the Library.

00:02:20.400 --> 00:02:23.430
On behalf of all of my
colleagues, it's a pleasure

00:02:23.430 --> 00:02:27.980
to welcome you to Stories
from a Fallen World.

00:02:27.980 --> 00:02:30.240
The Library of Congress' Prize

00:02:30.240 --> 00:02:34.800
for American Fiction
Tribute to Denis Johnson.

00:02:34.800 --> 00:02:38.380
Tonight is the third in what
has become an annual celebration

00:02:38.380 --> 00:02:41.590
of the prize and its winners.

00:02:41.590 --> 00:02:45.480
And I know that we all
find pleasure in the fact

00:02:45.480 --> 00:02:47.160
that in today's hectic world.

00:02:47.160 --> 00:02:51.360
We can pause and take an
evening to recognize the power

00:02:51.360 --> 00:02:55.900
of literature to
change our perceptions.

00:02:55.900 --> 00:02:58.260
Along with our Poet Laureate,

00:02:58.260 --> 00:03:01.710
the prize for American
Fiction stands

00:03:01.710 --> 00:03:05.790
as the Library's highest
honor to an American writer.

00:03:05.790 --> 00:03:09.810
It seeks to commend strong,
unique, enduring voices

00:03:09.810 --> 00:03:15.850
who have told us something new
about the American experience.

00:03:15.850 --> 00:03:18.920
Denis Johnson certainly
deserves the honor.

00:03:18.920 --> 00:03:20.660
As last year's prize winner,

00:03:20.660 --> 00:03:24.620
Marilynne Robinson
has said about him.

00:03:24.620 --> 00:03:28.970
"I have never known a writer who
was so identical with his work.

00:03:28.970 --> 00:03:33.350
Whose thoughts and passions
and energies were so entirely

00:03:33.350 --> 00:03:39.250
of one substance with the
world he remade as fiction."

00:03:39.250 --> 00:03:42.420
The great energy of his
imagination was a fusion

00:03:42.420 --> 00:03:44.330
of honesty and seriousness.

00:03:44.330 --> 00:03:46.520
Pain and laughter.

00:03:46.520 --> 00:03:49.700
His life was a thing of
the moment and urgency,

00:03:49.700 --> 00:03:52.940
pure and undistracted.

00:03:52.940 --> 00:03:57.060
Denis left us too soon, but
we have an amazing group

00:03:57.060 --> 00:04:00.970
of his writing peers,
literary and journalistic.

00:04:00.970 --> 00:04:05.240
Here with us tonight to help
celebrate his life and work.

00:04:05.240 --> 00:04:07.890
It should be a fascinating
discussion that reflects

00:04:07.890 --> 00:04:12.050
in strikingly different
ways the gritty themes

00:04:12.050 --> 00:04:15.380
that course through his stories.

00:04:15.380 --> 00:04:19.550
Before we get started, I'd like
to recognize Cindy Johnson,

00:04:19.550 --> 00:04:22.690
Denis' widow, and his
daughter, Lana Burke.

00:04:22.690 --> 00:04:27.330
We're so very glad that you
could join us this evening.

00:04:27.330 --> 00:04:31.070
I'd also like to recognize Avida
Basharad [assumed spelling],

00:04:31.070 --> 00:04:33.690
Deputy Publisher
of Random House.

00:04:33.690 --> 00:04:37.930
Random House is the proud
publisher of Denis' work.

00:04:37.930 --> 00:04:41.460
Now please let me welcome
my colleague John Haskell

00:04:41.460 --> 00:04:42.760
to the stage.

00:04:42.760 --> 00:04:46.080
To tell you just a bit about
one of our hosts this evening.

00:04:46.080 --> 00:04:49.530
The John W. Kluge Center
here at the Library.

00:04:49.530 --> 00:04:51.510
Thank you.

00:04:51.510 --> 00:04:58.610
[ Applause ]

00:04:58.610 --> 00:04:59.910
&gt;&gt; John Haskell:
Thank you, Jane.

00:04:59.910 --> 00:05:01.310
And thank you all for coming.

00:05:01.310 --> 00:05:06.150
The Kluge Center's proud to
be co-sponsor of this event.

00:05:06.150 --> 00:05:08.490
It's a continuation of a
collaboration we've had

00:05:08.490 --> 00:05:11.120
with the Poetry and
Literature Center.

00:05:11.120 --> 00:05:15.300
To celebrate the winners in
the Prize for American Fiction.

00:05:15.300 --> 00:05:20.000
The tribute to this particular
literary giant fits perfectly

00:05:20.000 --> 00:05:22.190
into the Kluge Center's mission.

00:05:22.190 --> 00:05:25.080
Which is to be a
bridge between scholars

00:05:25.080 --> 00:05:26.890
and writers on the one hand.

00:05:26.890 --> 00:05:30.710
And policy makers and the
interested public on the other.

00:05:30.710 --> 00:05:33.680
And that's to foster a
continuing conversation

00:05:33.680 --> 00:05:35.920
of the challenges
facing democracies

00:05:35.920 --> 00:05:37.920
in the twenty-first century.

00:05:37.920 --> 00:05:41.980
Before we get to the program, I
want to give a quick shout-out

00:05:41.980 --> 00:05:44.300
to the National Endowment
to the Humanities.

00:05:44.300 --> 00:05:49.660
Who's gotten the word out to, to
a lot of you about this event.

00:05:49.660 --> 00:05:51.430
And also to thank them
for the work they do

00:05:51.430 --> 00:05:53.710
in collaboration
with the Library.

00:05:53.710 --> 00:05:58.090
Right now we have a brief
video featuring Denis Johnson.

00:06:05.410 --> 00:06:07.790
&gt;&gt; "English words
are like prisms.

00:06:07.790 --> 00:06:10.230
Empty, nothing inside.

00:06:10.230 --> 00:06:12.340
And still they make rainbows."

00:06:12.340 --> 00:06:14.090
So says a character
in Already Dead.

00:06:14.090 --> 00:06:18.190
A novel by the late, great
American writer, Denis Johnson.

00:06:18.190 --> 00:06:21.180
Johnson's stories, as
legions of his fans know.

00:06:21.180 --> 00:06:23.020
Are also prisms.

00:06:23.020 --> 00:06:26.360
They are hard, merciless,
flinty,

00:06:26.360 --> 00:06:29.170
and yet they too make rainbows.

00:06:29.170 --> 00:06:32.000
He's been called a
writer's writer's writer.

00:06:32.000 --> 00:06:34.930
And for all the enigma
of that string of words,

00:06:34.930 --> 00:06:36.860
they hold a simple truth.

00:06:36.860 --> 00:06:39.980
Those who bring language
to life recognize Johnson's

00:06:39.980 --> 00:06:41.390
gifts instantly.

00:06:41.390 --> 00:06:46.190
Louise Erdrich calls his work
"profound" and "transcendent."

00:06:46.190 --> 00:06:48.970
Jonathan Franzen finds
his sentences "miracles

00:06:48.970 --> 00:06:51.220
of transparency and tone."

00:06:51.220 --> 00:06:55.590
Philip Roth calls him "daring,
terrifying, and an emissary

00:06:55.590 --> 00:06:57.760
for tortured, broken souls."

00:06:57.760 --> 00:07:01.700
Marilynne Robinson marvels that
a writer's personal passions

00:07:01.700 --> 00:07:03.220
and energies can be

00:07:03.220 --> 00:07:06.410
so inextricably wedded
to his words.

00:07:06.410 --> 00:07:11.050
All agree Denis Johnson has
managed to give us minimalist

00:07:11.050 --> 00:07:16.170
yet distinctly ecstatic and
hallucinatory rainbow prose.

00:07:16.170 --> 00:07:18.440
He is an American original.

00:07:18.440 --> 00:07:20.850
He was born in 1949
in Munich, Germany.

00:07:20.850 --> 00:07:24.950
And raised in Tokyo and Manila,
the child of American diplomats.

00:07:24.950 --> 00:07:27.280
As a teenager, moving
back to Washington,

00:07:27.280 --> 00:07:29.360
D.C. during the tumultuous
sixties,

00:07:29.360 --> 00:07:31.970
he came to know the country
and the restless characters.

00:07:31.970 --> 00:07:35.120
He would capture so
vividly in his fiction.

00:07:35.120 --> 00:07:36.710
He graduated in English
Literature

00:07:36.710 --> 00:07:38.380
from the University of Iowa.

00:07:38.380 --> 00:07:41.240
And earned an MFA from
the Iowa Writers' Workshop

00:07:41.240 --> 00:07:42.570
where he returned as a teacher.

00:07:42.570 --> 00:07:45.500
He has also taught at
Texas State University.

00:07:45.500 --> 00:07:48.280
And the University
of Texas at Austin.

00:07:48.280 --> 00:07:51.780
In the course of his fevered
career, he published novels,

00:07:51.780 --> 00:07:54.310
short stories, journalism,
and poetry.

00:07:54.310 --> 00:07:58.260
Among his best-known works
are those about the flotsam

00:07:58.260 --> 00:08:00.140
and jetsam of American life.

00:08:00.140 --> 00:08:01.960
The Laughing Monsters.

00:08:01.960 --> 00:08:03.960
Nobody Move.

00:08:03.960 --> 00:08:05.530
Tree of Smoke.

00:08:05.530 --> 00:08:07.120
Already Dead.

00:08:07.120 --> 00:08:08.650
Jesus' Son.

00:08:08.650 --> 00:08:12.750
Resuscitation of a Hanged
Man, The Stars at Noon.

00:08:12.750 --> 00:08:14.430
Fiskadoro.

00:08:14.430 --> 00:08:17.310
Angels. He's received
numerous award for these,

00:08:17.310 --> 00:08:21.380
including a National Book award,
a Lannan Fellowship in Fiction,

00:08:21.380 --> 00:08:26.280
a Whiting Writers' Award, and
in 2008 he was named a finalist

00:08:26.280 --> 00:08:27.670
for the Pulitzer Prize.

00:08:27.670 --> 00:08:30.090
Throughout, he had
chronicled an America

00:08:30.090 --> 00:08:33.290
that has gone unobserved,
unrecorded.

00:08:33.290 --> 00:08:38.280
Here are our drug addicts, our
war veterans, our disaffected.

00:08:38.280 --> 00:08:41.490
Our used up and left behind.

00:08:41.490 --> 00:08:44.820
And yet the most affecting
and rewarding aspect

00:08:44.820 --> 00:08:46.860
of Denis Johnson's fiction.

00:08:46.860 --> 00:08:49.620
Is that in work after
work he has proved

00:08:49.620 --> 00:08:53.450
that beauty often lurks
in unexpected places.

00:08:53.450 --> 00:08:55.910
That strength can
be found in failure.

00:08:55.910 --> 00:09:00.390
That the human spirit is a
fragile but resilient vessel.

00:09:00.390 --> 00:09:03.830
His is a very American story.

00:09:03.830 --> 00:09:07.240
He once described his works as
pressure cookers of language.

00:09:07.240 --> 00:09:11.100
His characters as those who
inhabit life's perilous edge.

00:09:11.100 --> 00:09:12.510
As time wore on, he found

00:09:12.510 --> 00:09:15.060
that he himself was
all too vulnerable

00:09:15.060 --> 00:09:16.500
to these human frailties.

00:09:16.500 --> 00:09:19.400
When the Librarian of
Congress, Carla Hayden,

00:09:19.400 --> 00:09:22.420
offered Denis Johnson the
Library of Congress Prize

00:09:22.420 --> 00:09:26.180
for American Fiction
in March of 2017.

00:09:26.180 --> 00:09:29.520
He wrote in an email
message, "My head is spinning

00:09:29.520 --> 00:09:31.580
from such great news."

00:09:31.580 --> 00:09:35.580
Two months later,
tragically, he was dead.

00:09:35.580 --> 00:09:36.880
The Library is very proud

00:09:36.880 --> 00:09:40.090
to honor posthumously this
extraordinary human being

00:09:40.090 --> 00:09:41.950
and writer whose contributions

00:09:41.950 --> 00:09:45.480
to the American canon have
been lasting and invaluable.

00:09:45.480 --> 00:09:48.070
As the Librarian wrote when
the prize was announced

00:09:48.070 --> 00:09:53.320
in June 2017, "Denis Johnson
was a writer for our times.

00:09:53.320 --> 00:09:56.210
In prose that fused
grace with grit.

00:09:56.210 --> 00:09:59.680
He spun tale after tale
about our walking wounded,

00:09:59.680 --> 00:10:03.100
the demons that haunt,
the salvation we seek.

00:10:03.100 --> 00:10:07.350
We emerge from his imagined
world with profound empathy,

00:10:07.350 --> 00:10:09.970
a different perspective,
a little changed."

00:10:09.970 --> 00:10:13.340
We are very proud to count Denis
Johnson among the distinguished

00:10:13.340 --> 00:10:14.980
winners of the Library

00:10:14.980 --> 00:10:18.510
of Congress Prize
for American Fiction.

00:10:18.510 --> 00:10:23.510
[ Music ]

00:10:23.510 --> 00:10:42.040
[ Applause ]

00:10:42.040 --> 00:10:44.360
&gt;&gt; Marie Arana: Good
evening, Ladies and Gentlemen.

00:10:44.360 --> 00:10:45.920
My name is Marie Arana.

00:10:45.920 --> 00:10:50.030
And I have the privilege
of serving as the Literary

00:10:50.030 --> 00:10:55.220
of Congress and to the Librarian
of Congress, Dr. Carla Hayden.

00:10:55.220 --> 00:10:58.770
One of my most rewarding
responsibilities is directing

00:10:58.770 --> 00:11:02.690
the jury that governs
this distinguished award.

00:11:02.690 --> 00:11:06.330
The Library of Congress
Prize for American Fiction.

00:11:06.330 --> 00:11:09.410
In that capacity, I get to
work with wonderful scholars

00:11:09.410 --> 00:11:10.720
like the ones you've just heard.

00:11:10.720 --> 00:11:14.300
Jane McAuliffe, and John
Haskell, as well as the head

00:11:14.300 --> 00:11:16.240
of the Poetry and
Literature Center,

00:11:16.240 --> 00:11:20.450
Rob Casper whom you'll meet
at the end of the program.

00:11:20.450 --> 00:11:25.000
Every year a jury of 27
distinguished literary critics,

00:11:25.000 --> 00:11:30.020
Nobel Laureates in Literature,
Man Booker Award winners.

00:11:30.020 --> 00:11:34.590
Former winners of this prize put
forward three American authors

00:11:34.590 --> 00:11:36.690
they think most deserving.

00:11:36.690 --> 00:11:40.440
The Librarian of Congress
makes the final selection.

00:11:40.440 --> 00:11:43.050
The purpose of that
award is spelled

00:11:43.050 --> 00:11:45.180
out on the back of
your programs.

00:11:45.180 --> 00:11:49.840
Is to commend strong,
unique, enduring voices.

00:11:49.840 --> 00:11:51.140
That throughout long,

00:11:51.140 --> 00:11:53.280
consistently accomplished
careers,

00:11:53.280 --> 00:11:57.800
have told us something new
about the American experience.

00:11:57.800 --> 00:12:02.280
Past awardees have been
Herman Wouk, Philip Roth,

00:12:02.280 --> 00:12:08.590
Isabel Allende, Don DeLillo,
E.L. Doctorow, Louise Erdrich,

00:12:08.590 --> 00:12:13.620
John Grisham, Marilynne
Robinson, and Toni Morrison.

00:12:13.620 --> 00:12:19.640
The choice of our tenth
prize winner, Denis Johnson,

00:12:19.640 --> 00:12:22.850
made by Dr. Hayden in
March of last year.

00:12:22.850 --> 00:12:27.050
And then confirmed in a
prize ceremony in September.

00:12:27.050 --> 00:12:31.330
Was especially thrilling for
me, as I've been a dedicated fan

00:12:31.330 --> 00:12:35.420
of Denis' work since I
stumbled onto Resuscitation

00:12:35.420 --> 00:12:38.410
of a Hanged Man, back
in the early nineties.

00:12:38.410 --> 00:12:41.440
When I was a little
younger than I am now.

00:12:41.440 --> 00:12:45.220
And found myself bowled
over by his language,

00:12:45.220 --> 00:12:47.610
its emotional force.

00:12:47.610 --> 00:12:49.860
Its precision.

00:12:49.860 --> 00:12:56.440
As one reviewer wrote, quote,
"His novels like poems seem

00:12:56.440 --> 00:12:59.640
to be written line to line."

00:12:59.640 --> 00:13:02.240
Unquote. But the full power

00:13:02.240 --> 00:13:06.800
of his stories transcends even
his considerable prose mastery.

00:13:06.800 --> 00:13:11.540
Denis' stories land
like a swift punch,

00:13:11.540 --> 00:13:15.480
somewhere between gut and heart.

00:13:15.480 --> 00:13:19.110
The last time I spoke to
Denis, it was on the phone.

00:13:19.110 --> 00:13:22.940
Trying to persuade him
to be here tonight.

00:13:22.940 --> 00:13:26.450
He had been so delighted by
Dr. Hayden's call and the news

00:13:26.450 --> 00:13:28.890
that he was the chosen honorees.

00:13:28.890 --> 00:13:33.820
I exchanged emails with
him just after that call.

00:13:33.820 --> 00:13:37.170
But he was also an
immensely private man.

00:13:37.170 --> 00:13:41.290
He didn't like public
expressions of admiration.

00:13:41.290 --> 00:13:43.750
Indeed he had been
conveniently away

00:13:43.750 --> 00:13:46.920
in some war zone
reporting a story

00:13:46.920 --> 00:13:49.860
when the National Book
Award was conferred

00:13:49.860 --> 00:13:51.760
on his ten years before.

00:13:51.760 --> 00:13:57.260
For his devastatingly
powerful work, Tree of Smoke.

00:13:57.260 --> 00:13:59.600
I tried valiantly
to argue my case

00:13:59.600 --> 00:14:02.020
that he should join us here.

00:14:02.020 --> 00:14:03.950
That he didn't need to do much.

00:14:03.950 --> 00:14:06.960
Just come, sit out there in
the audience with all of you

00:14:06.960 --> 00:14:09.650
and be lauded and celebrated.

00:14:09.650 --> 00:14:11.100
And given his due for being one

00:14:11.100 --> 00:14:16.130
of the great American
literary figures of our time.

00:14:16.130 --> 00:14:17.810
He was polite.

00:14:17.810 --> 00:14:19.520
He was friendly.

00:14:19.520 --> 00:14:22.660
He let me talk and talk.

00:14:22.660 --> 00:14:23.960
[Laughter] That phone call

00:14:23.960 --> 00:14:26.240
which lasted a good long
while, as I remember.

00:14:26.240 --> 00:14:29.230
And during which I felt
with every passing minute

00:14:29.230 --> 00:14:32.430
that my powers of
persuasion were failing me.

00:14:32.430 --> 00:14:37.560
Ended with, "Umm,
I don't think so."

00:14:37.560 --> 00:14:39.510
[Laughter] He just couldn't
bring himself to do it.

00:14:39.510 --> 00:14:45.030
That was on May 18, 2017.

00:14:45.030 --> 00:14:48.530
Six days later, he was gone.

00:14:48.530 --> 00:14:54.900
Now we're here, gathering
to honor him in his absence.

00:14:57.090 --> 00:15:00.520
Thinking about how best
to celebrate Denis.

00:15:00.520 --> 00:15:05.490
We decided that might please him
most, given his gimlet-eyed view

00:15:05.490 --> 00:15:07.990
of public expressions
of admiration.

00:15:07.990 --> 00:15:12.690
Might be to turn our lights
in the other direction.

00:15:12.690 --> 00:15:17.850
We decided to pay tribute to him
by honoring others in his name.

00:15:17.850 --> 00:15:22.210
Choosing three exemplary
American writers whose works

00:15:22.210 --> 00:15:25.140
reflect in one way or
another the themes that are

00:15:25.140 --> 00:15:28.200
so present in Denis' work.

00:15:28.200 --> 00:15:31.720
They would be excellent writers
at the top of their form.

00:15:31.720 --> 00:15:34.720
Very different practitioners
of the craft.

00:15:34.720 --> 00:15:38.350
Three greats who, like
Denis, tell stories,

00:15:38.350 --> 00:15:40.670
fiction or nonfiction.

00:15:43.640 --> 00:15:45.090
Excuse me.

00:15:45.090 --> 00:15:47.870
Stories of a Fallen World.

00:15:47.870 --> 00:15:51.340
The human costs of
addiction, for instance.

00:15:51.340 --> 00:15:54.180
The terrible fog of war.

00:15:54.180 --> 00:15:58.210
The essential alienation
and disconnectedness

00:15:58.210 --> 00:16:01.280
that define modern-day America.

00:16:01.280 --> 00:16:04.410
If we do this right, tonight
you'll see a little bit

00:16:04.410 --> 00:16:08.560
of Denis and his obsessions.

00:16:08.560 --> 00:16:12.160
In all three of these
brilliant wordsmiths.

00:16:12.160 --> 00:16:14.570
I'd like to tell you
something about each.

00:16:14.570 --> 00:16:17.880
Right up front, right
here before we sit down.

00:16:17.880 --> 00:16:20.360
In reverse order of
their appearance.

00:16:20.360 --> 00:16:22.460
So that when I actually
bring them on,

00:16:22.460 --> 00:16:24.790
the last shall be the first.

00:16:24.790 --> 00:16:28.440
Let me start in that
spirit with someone

00:16:28.440 --> 00:16:31.060
who will actually
follow the writers.

00:16:31.060 --> 00:16:34.660
She is Elizabeth Cuthrell, a
very accomplished film producer

00:16:34.660 --> 00:16:37.840
who wrote and produced the
film version of Jesus' Son

00:16:37.840 --> 00:16:44.660
that stark, searing, often
funny, quirkily funny collection

00:16:44.660 --> 00:16:48.080
of stories for which Denis
is probably best known.

00:16:48.080 --> 00:16:51.200
Elizabeth is co-founder
of Evenstar Films.

00:16:51.200 --> 00:16:54.050
An independent film and
theater production company.

00:16:54.050 --> 00:16:56.620
She's turned out numerous
prize-winning movies as well

00:16:56.620 --> 00:17:00.000
as acclaimed theater
productions on both coasts.

00:17:00.000 --> 00:17:02.130
She also produced a
stunning series of,

00:17:02.130 --> 00:17:03.970
of public service announcements.

00:17:03.970 --> 00:17:06.380
Called Stop the Hate.

00:17:06.380 --> 00:17:08.930
You're urging racial tolerance,

00:17:08.930 --> 00:17:12.510
for which she won
the Courage Award.

00:17:12.510 --> 00:17:17.060
We're especially thankful, very
grateful to Elizabeth for coming

00:17:17.060 --> 00:17:22.520
to share with us her long-time
friendship with Denis Johnson.

00:17:22.520 --> 00:17:29.260
Sam Quinones is the author of
Dreamland, a true masterpiece

00:17:29.260 --> 00:17:32.450
of journalism about
the opioid crisis

00:17:32.450 --> 00:17:34.220
and the widespread addiction

00:17:34.220 --> 00:17:38.330
that has ravaged small town
America and the heartland.

00:17:38.330 --> 00:17:44.300
His book is powerful, absorbing,
urgent, a monumental achievement

00:17:44.300 --> 00:17:48.600
that drills down on the harsh
realities that Denis described

00:17:48.600 --> 00:17:50.860
so memorably in fiction.

00:17:50.860 --> 00:17:53.230
The winner of the National
Book Critics' Circle Award,

00:17:53.230 --> 00:17:56.600
a finalist for the
L.A. Times Book Prize.

00:17:56.600 --> 00:18:00.080
And named one of the
best books of 2015,

00:18:00.080 --> 00:18:04.840
it's a book every
American should read.

00:18:04.840 --> 00:18:07.650
A book that tracks a
spiraling drug trade.

00:18:07.650 --> 00:18:12.200
A voracious, unfettered
pharmaceutical industry.

00:18:12.200 --> 00:18:17.090
And hundreds of thousands of
lives strewn along the way.

00:18:17.090 --> 00:18:20.370
We're very lucky to have
Sam with us tonight.

00:18:20.370 --> 00:18:24.980
Elliott Ackerman, a United
States Marine served five tours

00:18:24.980 --> 00:18:26.280
of duty in Iraq.

00:18:26.280 --> 00:18:29.750
And Afghanistan, and is the
recipient of the Silver Star,

00:18:29.750 --> 00:18:33.650
the Bronze Star for valor,
and the Purple Heart.

00:18:33.650 --> 00:18:36.900
His essays and short stories
have appeared in the New Yorker,

00:18:36.900 --> 00:18:39.780
the Atlantic, the New
Republic, among many others.

00:18:39.780 --> 00:18:44.400
His first book, Green on
Blue, is a harrowing, brutal,

00:18:44.400 --> 00:18:48.490
utterly absorbing novel about
an Afghan orphan trapped

00:18:48.490 --> 00:18:51.630
in the savage fog of war.

00:18:51.630 --> 00:18:54.770
Elliot's second novel,
Dark at the Crossing,

00:18:54.770 --> 00:18:56.540
published just last year.

00:18:56.540 --> 00:18:59.020
Is about a young
Arab American caught

00:18:59.020 --> 00:19:01.290
in the Syrian conflagration.

00:19:01.290 --> 00:19:04.630
The novel was a finalist
for the National Book Award.

00:19:04.630 --> 00:19:07.680
And named one of the
best books of 2017.

00:19:07.680 --> 00:19:11.270
He'll publish a new novel this
fall called Waiting for Eden

00:19:11.270 --> 00:19:14.040
about an American
veteran home from the war.

00:19:14.040 --> 00:19:19.410
Drastically damaged in
mind, spirit, and body.

00:19:19.410 --> 00:19:22.450
Elliot, it's great
to have you here.

00:19:22.450 --> 00:19:25.090
Jonathan Franzen, our
first guest tonight,

00:19:25.090 --> 00:19:27.630
is renowned for plumbing
the depths

00:19:27.630 --> 00:19:30.910
of the modern American psyche.

00:19:30.910 --> 00:19:34.730
He is a past master of the
essential loneliness and anxiety

00:19:34.730 --> 00:19:36.570
that permeates contemporary
life.

00:19:36.570 --> 00:19:42.670
And the wild, careening twists
of fate that can throw it all

00:19:42.670 --> 00:19:46.030
out of whack, and
send it spinning.

00:19:46.030 --> 00:19:48.860
Jon's talent for forming
striking narratives

00:19:48.860 --> 00:19:53.000
out of ordinary life is
abundantly evident in his work.

00:19:53.000 --> 00:19:57.020
Most recently in his richly
imagined novel, Purity.

00:19:57.020 --> 00:19:59.930
Which has been called
his most fleet-footed,

00:19:59.930 --> 00:20:03.050
intimate novel yet.

00:20:03.050 --> 00:20:06.550
"If some authors are
masters of suspense,

00:20:06.550 --> 00:20:09.180
others post-modern
verbal acrobats,"

00:20:09.180 --> 00:20:10.740
Publisher's Weekly wrote.

00:20:10.740 --> 00:20:15.050
"And still others complex
character pointillists,

00:20:15.050 --> 00:20:18.780
few excel in all three arenas."

00:20:18.780 --> 00:20:20.810
Jon is the authors
of four other novels.

00:20:20.810 --> 00:20:24.200
Among them, Freedom
and the Corrections,

00:20:24.200 --> 00:20:26.600
for which he won a
National Book Award.

00:20:26.600 --> 00:20:28.700
And numerous other prizes.

00:20:28.700 --> 00:20:32.310
And five works of
nonfiction and translation.

00:20:32.310 --> 00:20:36.510
Ladies and gentlemen, will you
please welcome Jonathan Franzen?

00:20:36.510 --> 00:20:49.060
[ Applause ]

00:20:49.060 --> 00:20:52.610
So I'd like to start
with a quote, Jon.

00:20:52.610 --> 00:20:54.410
If everyone can hear me.

00:20:54.410 --> 00:20:55.710
Can I, can I be heard?

00:20:55.710 --> 00:21:01.230
Yes? This is from Sam
Tanenhaus at the New York Times.

00:21:01.230 --> 00:21:04.260
He said, "Franzen cracks
open the opaque shell

00:21:04.260 --> 00:21:06.210
of postmodernism.

00:21:06.210 --> 00:21:09.290
Tweezes out its tangled
circuitry,

00:21:09.290 --> 00:21:13.240
and inserts in its place,
the warm beating heart

00:21:13.240 --> 00:21:15.370
of an authentic humanism."

00:21:15.370 --> 00:21:18.510
&gt;&gt; Jonathan Franzen:
That was nice of Sam.

00:21:18.510 --> 00:21:21.740
[ Laughter ]

00:21:21.740 --> 00:21:25.490
&gt;&gt; Marie Arana: "He writes with
equal fluency on equity finance,

00:21:25.490 --> 00:21:29.110
railroad engineering, currency
manipulation in Eastern Europe.

00:21:29.110 --> 00:21:32.050
The neurochemistry of
clinical depression.

00:21:32.050 --> 00:21:34.370
But the data flows through
the arteries of narrative.

00:21:34.370 --> 00:21:37.470
Attending to the quiet
drama of interior life

00:21:37.470 --> 00:21:39.710
and recording its
fraught transactions

00:21:39.710 --> 00:21:41.010
with a public world."

00:21:41.010 --> 00:21:45.320
Now that is a pretty
big, tall order.

00:21:45.320 --> 00:21:50.010
Jon, you write about
dysfunctional families.

00:21:50.010 --> 00:21:55.780
Small American worlds that are
exploded really by large events.

00:21:55.780 --> 00:21:59.550
I think I can summarize
your work that way.

00:21:59.550 --> 00:22:04.790
And the humdrum of, of quiet
lives that are suddenly ripped

00:22:04.790 --> 00:22:08.680
to shreds by foreign
events or economic busts.

00:22:08.680 --> 00:22:10.490
Or miscommunications.

00:22:10.490 --> 00:22:11.790
Of happenstance.

00:22:11.790 --> 00:22:17.510
What brings you to
those subjects?

00:22:17.510 --> 00:22:23.270
[ Laughter ]

00:22:23.270 --> 00:22:24.570
&gt;&gt; Jonathan Franzen:
Sheer desperation.

00:22:24.570 --> 00:22:27.440
That's kind of what you face
every morning in the office.

00:22:27.440 --> 00:22:33.410
First of all, thank
you all for coming.

00:22:33.410 --> 00:22:37.280
I, I never do these things.

00:22:37.280 --> 00:22:40.480
There's only one writer I
would have done this for.

00:22:40.480 --> 00:22:42.380
And that's Denis
Johnson because he has,

00:22:42.380 --> 00:22:45.670
he has a unique place, actually.

00:22:45.670 --> 00:22:49.500
In the world of American
literature.

00:22:49.500 --> 00:22:54.170
He's the one writer who every
writer I know can quote multiple

00:22:54.170 --> 00:22:56.240
lines from verbatim.

00:22:56.240 --> 00:22:58.540
They are often very funny lines.

00:22:58.540 --> 00:23:00.820
Which is something I
hope we don't lose sight

00:23:00.820 --> 00:23:04.670
of as Denis was one of the
funniest writers we had.

00:23:04.670 --> 00:23:06.610
Laugh-out-loud funny.

00:23:06.610 --> 00:23:11.070
Precisely because he was
so close to the edge.

00:23:11.070 --> 00:23:13.230
So it's, it's an
honor to be here,

00:23:13.230 --> 00:23:15.980
and I'm so glad Cindy
can be here too.

00:23:17.350 --> 00:23:18.970
So oh, yeah.

00:23:18.970 --> 00:23:21.270
My work. [Clears throat]

00:23:27.070 --> 00:23:28.550
It's autobiographical.

00:23:28.550 --> 00:23:32.600
It's just to get at the
stuff that I'm interested in.

00:23:32.600 --> 00:23:35.110
I, I, I'm very bad at
writing about myself.

00:23:35.110 --> 00:23:36.600
I think there are
two kinds of writers.

00:23:36.600 --> 00:23:39.730
One who can pretty much only
write about himself or herself.

00:23:39.730 --> 00:23:44.430
And then the other kind
and I'm the other kind.

00:23:44.430 --> 00:23:49.810
And I, I like a good story.

00:23:49.810 --> 00:23:57.570
And typically, good stories are
about characters who want stuff.

00:23:57.570 --> 00:24:01.760
And also if they're anxious,
then the story might be funny.

00:24:01.760 --> 00:24:04.160
And if, if I'm not laughing,

00:24:04.160 --> 00:24:06.400
then I am just setting
those pages aside

00:24:06.400 --> 00:24:09.730
and trying something else.

00:24:09.730 --> 00:24:11.200
And I, and I guess, yes.

00:24:11.200 --> 00:24:13.410
And I always paid
attention to the news.

00:24:13.410 --> 00:24:19.500
I had a dad who was very attuned
to, he was just, he'd had no,

00:24:19.500 --> 00:24:20.990
he had no education really.

00:24:20.990 --> 00:24:23.000
Except, as a, as
a civil engineer.

00:24:23.000 --> 00:24:25.540
But he, he thought about stuff.

00:24:25.540 --> 00:24:29.030
And you know, dinner table
conversation when I was growing

00:24:29.030 --> 00:24:32.030
up would be what was
happening in the world.

00:24:32.030 --> 00:24:33.560
So that just seemed natural.

00:24:33.560 --> 00:24:36.020
And also it's nice if you have
a character who wants something

00:24:36.020 --> 00:24:39.690
to put it, to put that character
in a recognizable world.

00:24:39.690 --> 00:24:43.610
And I, it doesn't seem,
it just seems like yeah.

00:24:43.610 --> 00:24:44.910
It's, it's what I do.

00:24:44.910 --> 00:24:48.760
That was a sort of
inarticulate response.

00:24:48.760 --> 00:24:50.760
But the articulate
response would eat

00:24:50.760 --> 00:24:53.800
up the rest of our time.

00:24:53.800 --> 00:24:55.100
&gt;&gt; Marie Arana: Well,

00:24:55.100 --> 00:24:58.040
you're pretty articulate
on the page, Jon.

00:24:58.040 --> 00:25:00.460
&gt;&gt; Jonathan Franzen:
Where it counts.

00:25:00.460 --> 00:25:01.760
[Laughter]

00:25:01.760 --> 00:25:03.060
&gt;&gt; Marie Arana: Where it counts.

00:25:03.060 --> 00:25:07.530
The but you, you, you
really do, I think,

00:25:07.530 --> 00:25:10.990
more than many American writers

00:25:10.990 --> 00:25:14.540
who are dealing perhaps
with, you know.

00:25:14.540 --> 00:25:24.600
Plot-driven or, or shall we
say small domestic troubles.

00:25:24.600 --> 00:25:26.950
That there is a sense
that, there is a sense

00:25:26.950 --> 00:25:32.040
when you read Jonathan Franzen
that you are reading something

00:25:32.040 --> 00:25:34.280
about this anxious age.

00:25:34.280 --> 00:25:41.390
Something about a, a kind of
loss of connectivity that we've,

00:25:41.390 --> 00:25:44.800
that we seem to have come to.

00:25:44.800 --> 00:25:46.970
At least that's what
the critics say.

00:25:46.970 --> 00:25:49.560
What do you say from your perch?

00:25:49.560 --> 00:25:55.050
About what you're trying to do?

00:25:55.050 --> 00:25:57.180
&gt;&gt; Jonathan Franzen: Honestly,
I am trying to be funny.

00:25:57.180 --> 00:26:00.750
And I, and I find people who are
anxious very funny because I,

00:26:00.750 --> 00:26:03.490
I feel that's the only way
to survive my own anxiety.

00:26:03.490 --> 00:26:06.740
Is to step back and throw
it into somebody else,

00:26:06.740 --> 00:26:08.040
and then laugh at that person.

00:26:08.040 --> 00:26:13.990
So for instance, like
in the Corrections, I,

00:26:13.990 --> 00:26:18.080
I spent so I'm always looking
for a topic sentence that,

00:26:18.080 --> 00:26:20.920
this is a little craft thing.

00:26:20.920 --> 00:26:22.360
I don't really have a character

00:26:22.360 --> 00:26:25.040
until I can write a good topic
sentence about that character.

00:26:25.040 --> 00:26:27.490
It all goes back to what we
were taught in seventh grade

00:26:27.490 --> 00:26:29.830
about topic sentences.

00:26:29.830 --> 00:26:32.110
It turns out to be
really, really true.

00:26:32.110 --> 00:26:35.100
And it, and it can take
up to five years to come

00:26:35.100 --> 00:26:37.990
up with a topic sentence for
a character for me [laughter].

00:26:37.990 --> 00:26:41.020
But there was a character
in The Corrections, Gary,

00:26:41.020 --> 00:26:44.750
who and it was a rather
elaborate topic sentence,

00:26:44.750 --> 00:26:46.050
but it basically had to do with.

00:26:46.050 --> 00:26:49.260
He had, there was all this
attention in the nineties

00:26:49.260 --> 00:26:52.530
on clinical depression.

00:26:52.530 --> 00:26:57.460
Which Prozac was the,
the miracle cure for.

00:26:57.460 --> 00:27:02.700
And he, he basically he
was trying to demonstrate

00:27:02.700 --> 00:27:04.000
that he was not clinically.

00:27:04.000 --> 00:27:07.020
He was trying to do something in
order to demonstrate to his wife

00:27:07.020 --> 00:27:09.010
that he was not clinically
depressed.

00:27:09.010 --> 00:27:12.530
So that's, that was right
very much of the time.

00:27:12.530 --> 00:27:15.030
And there were, people
were having conversations--

00:27:15.030 --> 00:27:16.330
it became.

00:27:16.330 --> 00:27:17.630
Instead of saying, "I don't,

00:27:17.630 --> 00:27:18.930
I wish you would take the trash
out, or I wish you would clean

00:27:18.930 --> 00:27:20.320
up after dinner more."

00:27:20.320 --> 00:27:21.760
They would say, "You
have a problem,

00:27:21.760 --> 00:27:23.060
You're clinically depressed."

00:27:23.060 --> 00:27:24.390
And then the other
person would say, "No,

00:27:24.390 --> 00:27:25.690
I'm not clinically depressed.

00:27:25.690 --> 00:27:28.990
You're clinically depressed."

00:27:28.990 --> 00:27:32.890
[Laughter] And so
it was hilarious

00:27:32.890 --> 00:27:34.200
but those were real fights.

00:27:34.200 --> 00:27:36.470
And I had been in one myself.

00:27:36.470 --> 00:27:38.270
It was like-- .

00:27:38.270 --> 00:27:41.250
[ Laughter ]

00:27:41.250 --> 00:27:45.020
Yeah, so it's like
okay, well now I kind

00:27:45.020 --> 00:27:46.330
of got a handle on this guy.

00:27:46.330 --> 00:27:49.910
That the, and, and yes,
it does, it does draw

00:27:49.910 --> 00:27:52.500
in what's happening
in the world.

00:27:52.500 --> 00:27:54.630
Because why not?

00:27:54.630 --> 00:27:56.010
It's fun. Yeah.

00:27:56.010 --> 00:27:58.450
I, I mean, I'm an entertainer.

00:27:58.450 --> 00:28:00.280
I'm looking for what's fun.

00:28:00.280 --> 00:28:01.790
&gt;&gt; Marie Arana: So
let me ask you now.

00:28:01.790 --> 00:28:07.140
Talking about real life because
one of the things that I,

00:28:07.140 --> 00:28:10.890
I think would be
really interesting

00:28:10.890 --> 00:28:13.080
to explore particularly
with your work.

00:28:13.080 --> 00:28:17.110
Is the, is the way that
fiction in some ways gets

00:28:17.110 --> 00:28:24.380
across a reality better than
sometimes nonfiction can.

00:28:24.380 --> 00:28:28.530
What does fiction in
your mind, what does it,

00:28:28.530 --> 00:28:30.890
how does it do that
for a society?

00:28:30.890 --> 00:28:32.190
How does it feed us?

00:28:32.190 --> 00:28:35.800
How does it, how does it
nurture us in that sense?

00:28:35.800 --> 00:28:37.360
&gt;&gt; Jonathan Franzen: I
actually think the people

00:28:37.360 --> 00:28:41.660
who read Denis Johnson-level
fiction are the lucky ones.

00:28:41.660 --> 00:28:44.830
And I don't mean
economically the lucky ones.

00:28:44.830 --> 00:28:46.130
I mean just lucky.

00:28:46.130 --> 00:28:47.430
Something is going right

00:28:47.430 --> 00:28:49.990
if you can actually sustain
attention in a novel.

00:28:49.990 --> 00:28:54.360
If you're really, really
miserable, you can't do that.

00:28:54.360 --> 00:28:57.040
And in the prison population,
there are the readers,

00:28:57.040 --> 00:28:58.360
and those are the lucky ones.

00:28:58.360 --> 00:29:05.220
In any population it's,
it's actually so if you,

00:29:05.220 --> 00:29:07.520
if you could enjoy a book.

00:29:07.520 --> 00:29:10.340
You should pause for a
moment with gratitude

00:29:10.340 --> 00:29:11.640
that you're able to do that.

00:29:11.640 --> 00:29:12.940
Because a lot of people can't.

00:29:12.940 --> 00:29:14.240
If you can enjoy a
complicated dark book,

00:29:14.240 --> 00:29:16.330
that laughs at other things,

00:29:16.330 --> 00:29:20.600
at things other people
might find terrible.

00:29:20.600 --> 00:29:22.260
Then you're really,
really lucky.

00:29:22.260 --> 00:29:25.530
But that, but that is actually
almost a definition of,

00:29:25.530 --> 00:29:28.120
of what we call literature.

00:29:28.120 --> 00:29:31.480
Is that kind of cosmic
distance on stuff.

00:29:31.480 --> 00:29:34.810
If you're really down in the
trenches, you can't do that.

00:29:34.810 --> 00:29:41.670
Oh yeah, so I think of, I talk
a lot about the metamorphosis,

00:29:41.670 --> 00:29:45.460
Kafka's novel about Gregor
Samsa who wakes up one morning

00:29:45.460 --> 00:29:47.210
and finds that he's an insect.

00:29:47.210 --> 00:29:52.670
He could have done a memoir, a
sort of midstream memoir talking

00:29:52.670 --> 00:29:55.140
about how crappy it was to
live at home with his parents.

00:29:55.140 --> 00:29:58.210
And not even have
the good bedroom,

00:29:58.210 --> 00:30:00.670
even though he was
the son and so forth.

00:30:00.670 --> 00:30:03.910
[Laughter] As a grown
man, you know,

00:30:03.910 --> 00:30:05.330
he's been working
a job for years.

00:30:05.330 --> 00:30:07.950
And there he is at
home with the parents.

00:30:07.950 --> 00:30:13.330
And he could have
probably gotten across some

00:30:13.330 --> 00:30:16.040
of why he found that a drag.

00:30:16.040 --> 00:30:21.500
But to get at really the
degree to which he experienced

00:30:21.500 --> 00:30:27.790
that as unbelievably
terrible, he made up a story.

00:30:27.790 --> 00:30:29.090
He invented something.

00:30:29.090 --> 00:30:32.860
And, and also in the, in the
process, good thing for fiction,

00:30:32.860 --> 00:30:34.160
he protected his family.

00:30:34.160 --> 00:30:37.190
Because [laughter] everyone knew

00:30:37.190 --> 00:30:41.680
that the Kafka's did not
have a large bug for a son.

00:30:41.680 --> 00:30:45.880
So they, the parents
said, "Oh, it's not us."

00:30:46.990 --> 00:30:49.030
[Laughter] How could that be us?

00:30:49.030 --> 00:30:53.600
Franz is a little weird,
but he's not an insect.

00:30:55.360 --> 00:30:59.020
[Laughter] So and I think
that broadly speaking,

00:30:59.020 --> 00:31:00.840
that's a metaphor for
what fiction does.

00:31:00.840 --> 00:31:06.030
Is it, it enables you
to, to go, to exaggerate

00:31:06.030 --> 00:31:14.770
in these wild ways that, that
mere representation of reality.

00:31:14.770 --> 00:31:18.600
The states of mind, states,
emotional states and lots

00:31:18.600 --> 00:31:21.900
of other kinds of states.

00:31:21.900 --> 00:31:26.620
That mere factual
representation simply cannot.

00:31:26.620 --> 00:31:27.920
&gt;&gt; Marie Arana: Yeah.

00:31:27.920 --> 00:31:30.800
Of course that brings me,
you're, you're, you're talking

00:31:30.800 --> 00:31:35.400
about the, the ways
that fiction works.

00:31:35.400 --> 00:31:40.800
I mean, the humor in fiction
which, which Denis used

00:31:40.800 --> 00:31:44.350
so superbly in the
middle the darkest sort

00:31:44.350 --> 00:31:46.480
of funkiest moments.

00:31:46.480 --> 00:31:50.220
It would, you would find
it screamingly funny.

00:31:50.220 --> 00:31:52.670
&gt;&gt; Jonathan Franzen: His word
choice in a Fatal Accident,

00:31:52.670 --> 00:31:54.260
the first story in Jesus' Son.

00:31:54.260 --> 00:31:59.560
Even I think, I think, when
the, when the car crash happens,

00:31:59.560 --> 00:32:03.420
the woman says, "No," the
woman said viciously."

00:32:03.420 --> 00:32:04.890
Like that word viciously.

00:32:04.890 --> 00:32:11.750
Which is like a head-on
crash is about to occur.

00:32:11.750 --> 00:32:19.070
Yeah. That's, that tells me
he had resolved something.

00:32:19.070 --> 00:32:24.260
And could see it from the kind
of perspective from which-- .

00:32:24.260 --> 00:32:27.690
On the one hand, he's sort
of touching close to God.

00:32:27.690 --> 00:32:28.990
And on the other hand,

00:32:28.990 --> 00:32:33.020
he's touching his,
it's all hilarious.

00:32:33.020 --> 00:32:36.760
If you, if you get the new story
collection for no other reason,

00:32:36.760 --> 00:32:38.540
there's a two and
a half page scene

00:32:38.540 --> 00:32:43.250
of the narrator having
a knee examination.

00:32:43.250 --> 00:32:48.080
In surgical theater while
tripping on LSD that,

00:32:48.080 --> 00:32:51.500
if there's any doubt that
he was a comic writer.

00:32:51.500 --> 00:32:52.800
Yeah.

00:32:52.800 --> 00:32:54.760
&gt;&gt; Marie Arana: In
fact you, you,

00:32:54.760 --> 00:32:58.970
you made a wonderful citation
at his prize ceremony.

00:32:58.970 --> 00:33:02.550
And I want to read
at least part of it.

00:33:02.550 --> 00:33:06.110
You said, "His sentences at best
are miracles of transparency

00:33:06.110 --> 00:33:07.730
and tone," which
we've already heard.

00:33:07.730 --> 00:33:10.520
"Perfect in the way they inhabit
the page, but devoid of vanity

00:33:10.520 --> 00:33:11.930
about their perfection.

00:33:11.930 --> 00:33:14.270
Always vivid in their
reference to the actual

00:33:14.270 --> 00:33:17.760
but also always conveying
something larger.

00:33:17.760 --> 00:33:21.160
Their creator's own
self-knowledge and compassion

00:33:21.160 --> 00:33:23.590
and sense of cosmic comedy.

00:33:23.590 --> 00:33:27.720
The God I want to believe in
has a voice like Johnson's."

00:33:27.720 --> 00:33:29.140
&gt;&gt; Jonathan Franzen: Right.

00:33:29.140 --> 00:33:31.230
&gt;&gt; Marie Arana: What is-- .

00:33:31.230 --> 00:33:33.420
[Laughter]

00:33:33.420 --> 00:33:34.720
&gt;&gt; Jonathan Franzen:
Oh, I don't know.

00:33:34.720 --> 00:33:36.180
Stress on "want to".

00:33:36.180 --> 00:33:39.090
As in wish I could.

00:33:39.090 --> 00:33:42.280
But yeah, if, I mean, if there
were a God who spoke like,

00:33:42.280 --> 00:33:45.120
you know, in with that kind of.

00:33:45.120 --> 00:33:49.390
I'm not going to try to
explicate that sentence.

00:33:49.390 --> 00:33:50.690
&gt;&gt; Marie Arana: Okay.

00:33:50.690 --> 00:33:51.990
[Laughter] I think
what it meant-- .

00:33:51.990 --> 00:33:53.790
&gt;&gt; Jonathan Franzen: Thank you!

00:33:53.790 --> 00:33:58.120
[ Laughter ]

00:33:58.120 --> 00:33:59.420
&gt;&gt; Marie Arana: If I may.

00:33:59.420 --> 00:34:00.940
&gt;&gt; Jonathan Franzen:
Absolutely may.

00:34:00.940 --> 00:34:02.240
[Laughter]

00:34:02.240 --> 00:34:04.350
&gt;&gt; Marie Arana: Is that
he really had a voice.

00:34:04.350 --> 00:34:06.040
I mean a very strong voice.

00:34:06.040 --> 00:34:13.670
And it was, if, if, if we could
put a, if we could pinpoint

00:34:13.670 --> 00:34:17.210
that talent, it would be
that, that voice that he had.

00:34:17.210 --> 00:34:21.060
That was absolutely
unique and original.

00:34:21.060 --> 00:34:25.200
As yours is, I would say.

00:34:25.200 --> 00:34:33.640
That, that sense that, that
sense that you are in the hands

00:34:33.640 --> 00:34:39.810
of a really superb narrator
and you can't quite let go.

00:34:39.810 --> 00:34:41.600
It's mesmerizing.

00:34:41.600 --> 00:34:42.920
That voice.

00:34:42.920 --> 00:34:44.220
&gt;&gt; Jonathan Franzen:
Well thank you.

00:34:44.220 --> 00:34:45.520
&gt;&gt; Marie Arana: Is
that what you meant?

00:34:45.520 --> 00:34:46.820
[Laughter]

00:34:46.820 --> 00:34:48.120
&gt;&gt; Jonathan Franzen: I was
not talking about myself.

00:34:48.120 --> 00:34:49.420
I was talking about Denis.

00:34:49.420 --> 00:34:51.720
But.

00:34:53.420 --> 00:34:54.720
Yeah.

00:34:54.720 --> 00:34:56.020
&gt;&gt; Marie Arana: Yeah.

00:34:56.020 --> 00:34:57.990
&gt;&gt; Jonathan Franzen: What was--

00:34:57.990 --> 00:35:00.800
I, I thought actually that
Marilynne put it nicely,

00:35:00.800 --> 00:35:03.850
that there was, there is a
sense of a kind of unitary.

00:35:03.850 --> 00:35:06.240
That, that what he,
that the writing and,

00:35:06.240 --> 00:35:09.530
and the person were
almost indistinguishable.

00:35:09.530 --> 00:35:15.160
It strikes me and I think
our other two guests

00:35:15.160 --> 00:35:19.440
who will soon join
me can speak to this.

00:35:19.440 --> 00:35:22.710
He is somebody who might
very well not have survived.

00:35:22.710 --> 00:35:27.420
He was, he was a kind
of messed up kid.

00:35:27.420 --> 00:35:31.970
And had intimate knowledge with
these, you know, pretty violent

00:35:31.970 --> 00:35:35.460
and definitely addictive
situations.

00:35:35.460 --> 00:35:41.850
And there is a, there is
a sense of at the core

00:35:41.850 --> 00:35:43.150
of I think all of his.

00:35:43.150 --> 00:35:45.990
I, I was rereading The New
Stories on the way down here.

00:35:45.990 --> 00:35:49.560
And what, what the
whole book kind of feels

00:35:49.560 --> 00:35:53.530
like a meditation--
not a meditation.

00:35:53.530 --> 00:35:55.040
It's, it's a representation

00:35:55.040 --> 00:35:58.090
of the amazingness
of still being alive?

00:35:58.090 --> 00:36:03.770
So that there's something
about everything he wrote

00:36:03.770 --> 00:36:08.260
that is aware of the
proximity of death.

00:36:08.260 --> 00:36:11.660
And that, that goes to in
that respect there's a,

00:36:11.660 --> 00:36:13.770
I think there's a kind of
subterranean connection

00:36:13.770 --> 00:36:15.510
with Flannery O'Connor
who in her, the greatest

00:36:15.510 --> 00:36:20.480
of all of her great stories.

00:36:20.480 --> 00:36:24.070
Good Man is Hard to Find,

00:36:24.070 --> 00:36:26.430
she would have been a good woman
had there been someone there

00:36:26.430 --> 00:36:28.510
to shoot her every
day of her life.

00:36:28.510 --> 00:36:31.540
[ Laughter ]

00:36:31.540 --> 00:36:33.500
About the grandmother
in that story.

00:36:33.500 --> 00:36:37.270
If you don't know the
story, go read it.

00:36:37.270 --> 00:36:40.400
Which is basically this is,
this was a trivial woman

00:36:40.400 --> 00:36:45.690
who with a gun pointed at
her, suddenly found something.

00:36:45.690 --> 00:36:48.870
And somehow, throughout
his career,

00:36:48.870 --> 00:36:52.520
he managed to write the stuff
that felt right on that bubble

00:36:52.520 --> 00:36:54.120
of there's a gun pointed at me.

00:36:54.120 --> 00:36:56.230
Death is all around me.

00:36:56.230 --> 00:36:57.530
I've seen people die.

00:36:57.530 --> 00:36:59.980
I'm aware that I'm going to die.

00:36:59.980 --> 00:37:03.510
And you know, there's
a line in the new book,

00:37:03.510 --> 00:37:05.930
you know, "I like my wife.

00:37:05.930 --> 00:37:09.680
She's you know, clever
and rather attractive.

00:37:09.680 --> 00:37:11.210
She can die any minute."

00:37:11.210 --> 00:37:13.710
And then he just says that.

00:37:13.710 --> 00:37:15.010
It's like, and then
new paragraph,

00:37:15.010 --> 00:37:16.580
we're onto the rest
of the story.

00:37:16.580 --> 00:37:19.960
But that's, that seemed to me
kind of the essence of the work.

00:37:19.960 --> 00:37:22.830
That's why, what makes
it so exciting is

00:37:22.830 --> 00:37:26.320
that there's always
death right there.

00:37:26.320 --> 00:37:27.620
&gt;&gt; Marie Arana: Right there.

00:37:27.620 --> 00:37:28.920
&gt;&gt; Jonathan Franzen: Yeah.

00:37:28.920 --> 00:37:30.220
Right there.

00:37:30.220 --> 00:37:31.520
&gt;&gt; Marie Arana: Well,
with death right there,

00:37:31.520 --> 00:37:34.510
let's bring on Elliot Ackerman.

00:37:34.510 --> 00:37:45.140
[ Applause ]

00:37:45.140 --> 00:37:46.440
So here's a quote.

00:37:46.440 --> 00:37:47.740
&gt;&gt; Elliot Ackerman:
First of all,

00:37:47.740 --> 00:37:50.040
that might be my
favorite introduction.

00:37:51.330 --> 00:37:54.170
&gt;&gt; Marie Arana: Here, here's
a quote to accompany you

00:37:54.170 --> 00:37:55.470
to have you accompany us.

00:37:55.470 --> 00:37:58.340
As, as I did for Jon.

00:37:58.340 --> 00:38:00.360
This is from Ben Fountain,

00:38:00.360 --> 00:38:03.200
who wrote a wonderful book
called Billy Lynn's Wonderful

00:38:03.200 --> 00:38:05.640
Halftime Walk, if you know it.

00:38:05.640 --> 00:38:08.560
And he wrote about Elliot this.

00:38:08.560 --> 00:38:11.590
"Dark at the Crossing is every
bit as taut and harrowing

00:38:11.590 --> 00:38:13.290
as the place it depicts.

00:38:13.290 --> 00:38:16.190
A region where 15 years
of relentless war play

00:38:16.190 --> 00:38:20.090
out in filthy refugee camps
and upscale shopping malls.

00:38:20.090 --> 00:38:23.160
Elliot Ackerman has written
a brilliant, admirably,

00:38:23.160 --> 00:38:26.660
merciless novel of broken
lives, broken places,

00:38:26.660 --> 00:38:31.180
and good intentions gone awry."

00:38:31.180 --> 00:38:34.460
Someone once said of you, if
I remember this correctly.

00:38:34.460 --> 00:38:41.100
That they, they don't award
medals of valor for writing.

00:38:41.100 --> 00:38:45.880
But maybe they should to you.

00:38:45.880 --> 00:38:51.090
There's a sense, Elliot, in
your books, both of them.

00:38:51.090 --> 00:38:53.090
That you have emerged
from the cauldron

00:38:53.090 --> 00:38:55.610
of hell to tell this story.

00:38:55.610 --> 00:38:59.100
How, this is going
to, this is going

00:38:59.100 --> 00:39:03.050
to make Jon's blood pressure
rise because I read somewhere

00:39:03.050 --> 00:39:04.680
that he hates this question.

00:39:04.680 --> 00:39:06.130
I'm going to ask this question.

00:39:06.130 --> 00:39:10.350
How autobiographical
are these stories?

00:39:10.350 --> 00:39:12.500
In the sense that you
have lived through any--

00:39:12.500 --> 00:39:14.660
of course you've lived
through, through,

00:39:14.660 --> 00:39:16.050
through the hell of war.

00:39:16.050 --> 00:39:20.650
But to what extent
are these from life?

00:39:20.650 --> 00:39:22.850
&gt;&gt; Elliot Ackerman: Well,
I mean, you know, my,

00:39:22.850 --> 00:39:25.390
my first book is, is the story

00:39:25.390 --> 00:39:27.400
of an Afghan who's
murdered by an American.

00:39:27.400 --> 00:39:29.510
It's all told from the
perspective of the Afghan.

00:39:29.510 --> 00:39:31.880
So that's not me.

00:39:31.880 --> 00:39:36.430
And you know my, my second novel
takes place in southern Turkey

00:39:36.430 --> 00:39:38.170
around the Syrian civil
war and it's a love story.

00:39:38.170 --> 00:39:39.470
But those characters aren't me.

00:39:39.470 --> 00:39:43.780
However, they are deeply
informed by my experience.

00:39:43.780 --> 00:39:45.940
And I don't think I could
extricate my experiences

00:39:45.940 --> 00:39:47.240
from the book.

00:39:47.240 --> 00:39:48.650
&gt;&gt; Marie Arana: Right,
but there's a, there,

00:39:48.650 --> 00:39:54.400
there is a sense, I think,
especially in Green on Blue.

00:39:54.400 --> 00:40:02.010
That you are, you're not
sure what side is which.

00:40:02.010 --> 00:40:05.300
It reminds me of revolutions

00:40:05.300 --> 00:40:08.710
in which the sides keep
changing all the time.

00:40:08.710 --> 00:40:12.410
Because people see the
battle's going this way,

00:40:12.410 --> 00:40:13.710
the battle's going that way.

00:40:13.710 --> 00:40:15.840
And they're going to run to
whatever side is winning.

00:40:15.840 --> 00:40:20.370
There's that, there's a, a,
that sense of divided loyalties

00:40:20.370 --> 00:40:22.300
or confused loyalties.

00:40:22.300 --> 00:40:24.300
And the fog of it
all in a sense.

00:40:24.300 --> 00:40:28.240
That, and that's clearly
something that you've seen.

00:40:28.240 --> 00:40:30.400
&gt;&gt; Elliot Ackerman: I mean,
it's something that I've seen

00:40:30.400 --> 00:40:32.170
and something that I admire.

00:40:32.170 --> 00:40:34.130
You know, in other
people's writing.

00:40:34.130 --> 00:40:35.920
It's something I admired
in Denis Johnson's writing.

00:40:35.920 --> 00:40:40.110
You know, the ability to take
extremely complex political

00:40:40.110 --> 00:40:43.650
events and make them
feel extremely personal.

00:40:43.650 --> 00:40:45.870
I think it's something
that, that fiction does.

00:40:45.870 --> 00:40:50.290
But then you get a, you know,
we were talking about you know,

00:40:50.290 --> 00:40:52.500
different sides of an issue.

00:40:52.500 --> 00:40:53.800
You know, in a war.

00:40:53.800 --> 00:40:55.100
Like for instance, there's a,

00:40:55.100 --> 00:40:57.450
what's the trope someone just
said to me the other day.

00:40:57.450 --> 00:40:59.960
Which is you know, you, maybe
it was said on television.

00:40:59.960 --> 00:41:01.260
You don't really know a person

00:41:01.260 --> 00:41:03.240
until you've been
divorced from them.

00:41:03.240 --> 00:41:05.930
Which is you know like
that' probably true.

00:41:05.930 --> 00:41:09.360
You know I would append to that
you don't really know a person

00:41:09.360 --> 00:41:10.660
until you know you've fought

00:41:10.660 --> 00:41:13.230
on the opposite side
of a war from them.

00:41:13.230 --> 00:41:15.320
And so I think there's sort of,

00:41:15.320 --> 00:41:16.870
and sometimes we'll see
you know, it's, you know,

00:41:16.870 --> 00:41:19.470
why are you so, you know
fascinated by the people

00:41:19.470 --> 00:41:20.880
on the other sides
of these conflicts?

00:41:20.880 --> 00:41:23.510
Well in some ways they're the
people that you know the best

00:41:23.510 --> 00:41:25.550
until you trot out
another tired trope.

00:41:25.550 --> 00:41:27.140
You know, write what you know.

00:41:27.140 --> 00:41:30.120
And you know, and oftentimes you
know, you know them the best.

00:41:30.120 --> 00:41:31.420
&gt;&gt; Marie Arana: Right.

00:41:31.420 --> 00:41:35.150
But I, I assume that in, in,
in particularly in, in Iraq

00:41:35.150 --> 00:41:40.140
and Afghanistan you are
fighting alongside people who,

00:41:40.140 --> 00:41:42.150
who are of that land.

00:41:42.150 --> 00:41:48.550
And with whom you have to,
you have to make bonds.

00:41:48.550 --> 00:41:54.630
I mean one thing I think that
you've said so eloquently.

00:41:54.630 --> 00:41:58.550
Is that a Marine is
trained to kill, right?

00:41:58.550 --> 00:42:00.890
But he also has to
be trained to love.

00:42:00.890 --> 00:42:05.420
And why? Because he has to
throw himself in the line

00:42:05.420 --> 00:42:08.250
of fire for his buddy.

00:42:08.250 --> 00:42:10.320
For his compatriot.

00:42:10.320 --> 00:42:15.250
For the person he's,
he's, he's fighting with.

00:42:15.250 --> 00:42:23.920
And that really interests me,
that notion of you know, you're,

00:42:23.920 --> 00:42:27.170
you're essentially
falling in love with,

00:42:27.170 --> 00:42:32.690
or loving a person who,
whose life is at risk.

00:42:32.690 --> 00:42:37.160
And who may, who
will die or may die.

00:42:37.160 --> 00:42:38.770
&gt;&gt; Elliot Ackerman: I think
it gets to sort of the,

00:42:38.770 --> 00:42:40.380
the topic of our panel here.

00:42:40.380 --> 00:42:44.290
And what is very unique in
Johnson's work is that he is

00:42:44.290 --> 00:42:47.210
so often on the edge, or I
would say it's also almost

00:42:47.210 --> 00:42:52.310
like this extremely thin
membrane that is translucent

00:42:52.310 --> 00:42:53.830
when you're standing
there right up against.

00:42:53.830 --> 00:42:56.640
You know, issues,
particularly issues

00:42:56.640 --> 00:42:58.050
of conflict, you know, in wars.

00:42:58.050 --> 00:42:59.500
And who are fascinated
by that subject.

00:42:59.500 --> 00:43:01.680
You know the difference
between, you know,

00:43:01.680 --> 00:43:04.530
love and violence
is so permeable.

00:43:04.530 --> 00:43:09.630
And so I mean I found
in my own experience.

00:43:09.630 --> 00:43:11.150
I have found in my
own experience in war.

00:43:11.150 --> 00:43:14.120
Even some, some of the great
ironies is that you know people,

00:43:14.120 --> 00:43:16.470
you know, are doing very,
very courageous things.

00:43:16.470 --> 00:43:17.770
Because they love one another.

00:43:17.770 --> 00:43:19.070
But the courageous things

00:43:19.070 --> 00:43:20.370
that they're doing are
incredibly violent.

00:43:20.370 --> 00:43:24.820
And so, so again, you're
constantly, you know, flipping.

00:43:24.820 --> 00:43:29.170
You know, permeating
that membrane.

00:43:29.170 --> 00:43:30.470
&gt;&gt; Marie Arana: Speaking
of membranes,

00:43:30.470 --> 00:43:34.770
the Darkness at the Crossing.

00:43:34.770 --> 00:43:39.660
Deal with, a, an Iraqi
who's actually born in Iraq,

00:43:39.660 --> 00:43:41.680
but he's an American citizen.

00:43:41.680 --> 00:43:45.060
We can't but wonder
as we read it.

00:43:45.060 --> 00:43:49.070
And he wonders it himself,
where his loyalties lie.

00:43:49.070 --> 00:43:52.810
And what it means to
be true to oneself

00:43:52.810 --> 00:43:55.080
when you have two
identities at work.

00:43:55.080 --> 00:43:56.950
Two nationalities at work.

00:43:56.950 --> 00:44:00.190
Two, you know, loyalties.

00:44:00.190 --> 00:44:03.920
And how did you get
to that subject?

00:44:03.920 --> 00:44:07.180
And how, how, how does that,
how did that come to you?

00:44:07.180 --> 00:44:08.480
&gt;&gt; Elliot Ackerman: Well
you know, this character

00:44:08.480 --> 00:44:11.840
who is an Arab American
basically decides he wants

00:44:11.840 --> 00:44:18.240
to go cross into Syria to, to
fight for the Free Syrian Army.

00:44:18.240 --> 00:44:21.040
And a lot of the book is about
unpacking his motivations.

00:44:21.040 --> 00:44:22.730
And actually kind of gets
to what Jon was just saying

00:44:22.730 --> 00:44:24.350
with the Flannery
O'Connor story.

00:44:24.350 --> 00:44:25.760
About needing the gun
pointed at your head.

00:44:25.760 --> 00:44:27.760
Which also reminds
me of the great scene

00:44:27.760 --> 00:44:29.800
in Stanley Kubrick's
Full Metal Jacket.

00:44:29.800 --> 00:44:32.360
About Animal Mother, the machine
gunner in the Marine platoon.

00:44:32.360 --> 00:44:34.510
And they say, you know,
Animal Mother's a great guy.

00:44:34.510 --> 00:44:36.160
He just needs someone to
throw hand grenades at him

00:44:36.160 --> 00:44:38.760
for the rest of his life.

00:44:38.760 --> 00:44:40.940
[Laughter] And so, you
know, this character,

00:44:40.940 --> 00:44:44.000
Harris [inaudible] is kind of
the, he's in the same position.

00:44:44.000 --> 00:44:47.480
But you know, and to
be honest with you.

00:44:47.480 --> 00:44:48.780
The, the, the thing
that was foremost

00:44:48.780 --> 00:44:50.600
in my mind wasn't anything that
happened to me in the wars.

00:44:50.600 --> 00:44:54.590
It was actually a
scene in Anna Karenina

00:44:54.590 --> 00:44:56.990
and the way Anna Karenina ends.

00:44:56.990 --> 00:44:59.450
And so and the spoiler alert--

00:44:59.450 --> 00:45:02.040
she throws herself in front of
a train and commits suicide.

00:45:02.040 --> 00:45:05.820
[Laughter] But, but you know,
I always felt like reading

00:45:05.820 --> 00:45:07.920
that book and getting
[inaudible] at like Vronsky,

00:45:07.920 --> 00:45:09.680
her lover, kind of
gets like a bad rap.

00:45:09.680 --> 00:45:12.010
I feel like, you know, like the
world's been tough on Vronsky.

00:45:12.010 --> 00:45:14.440
And if you recall,
the last you ever hear

00:45:14.440 --> 00:45:15.810
of Vronsky, he's been disgraced.

00:45:15.810 --> 00:45:17.110
He's an outcast from
society now.

00:45:17.110 --> 00:45:19.200
But the last we hear is like
you don't even see Vronsky.

00:45:19.200 --> 00:45:20.500
You don't, you don't
see Vronsky.

00:45:20.500 --> 00:45:22.090
You're just told by
another character

00:45:22.090 --> 00:45:26.100
that Vronsky was last seen on
a train heading to the caucasus

00:45:26.100 --> 00:45:28.630
to rejoin his regiment.

00:45:28.630 --> 00:45:31.520
And they don't say why and
of course he's on a train.

00:45:31.520 --> 00:45:32.840
Anna just threw herself
in front of train.

00:45:32.840 --> 00:45:35.240
And you know, Tolstoy
doesn't tell you the reasons.

00:45:35.240 --> 00:45:38.930
But it always fascinated me
is you know he could be going

00:45:38.930 --> 00:45:40.390
to rejoin his regiment.

00:45:40.390 --> 00:45:43.760
Because he thinks that some you
know battlefield heroics will be

00:45:43.760 --> 00:45:46.370
the way he can redeem himself.

00:45:46.370 --> 00:45:49.570
And integrate again
into society.

00:45:49.570 --> 00:45:52.600
Okay, or he could be
going there to basically.

00:45:52.600 --> 00:45:55.650
He could be on that train for
the same reasons, you know,

00:45:55.650 --> 00:45:56.950
as Anna ended herself.

00:45:56.950 --> 00:45:58.480
He'll be going off to
war to kill himself.

00:45:58.480 --> 00:45:59.860
And you don't know, and
you never get the answer

00:45:59.860 --> 00:46:01.330
from Tolstoy.

00:46:01.330 --> 00:46:05.130
And you know I have always
been fascinated that how,

00:46:05.130 --> 00:46:07.140
you know people can
engage in one act.

00:46:07.140 --> 00:46:10.070
People can go to war for,
for completely different,

00:46:10.070 --> 00:46:11.800
you know for reasons they
don't even know themselves.

00:46:11.800 --> 00:46:13.290
And they can be an
act, a redemptive act.

00:46:13.290 --> 00:46:14.900
Or it can be a destructive act.

00:46:14.900 --> 00:46:16.280
So that's something
that you know that,

00:46:16.280 --> 00:46:18.530
that I was hoping to examine.

00:46:18.530 --> 00:46:22.070
&gt;&gt; Marie Arana: Well,
you, you as, as,

00:46:22.070 --> 00:46:24.110
as Denis did in,
in Tree of Smoke.

00:46:24.110 --> 00:46:28.130
That, that sense of
you know the, the,

00:46:28.130 --> 00:46:35.670
the complete suspension in a
kind of wildcard situation.

00:46:35.670 --> 00:46:39.120
&gt;&gt; Elliot Ackerman: Well like in
Angels, you know, which is one

00:46:39.120 --> 00:46:40.430
of my favorite books of his.

00:46:40.430 --> 00:46:44.280
You know you have this
sort of like kind of.

00:46:44.280 --> 00:46:46.210
It's not banal, but it
seems like everyday.

00:46:46.210 --> 00:46:47.510
It opens on a bus.

00:46:47.510 --> 00:46:48.810
I mean, you know, there's a guy,

00:46:48.810 --> 00:46:50.110
you know who's meeting
a woman on a bus.

00:46:50.110 --> 00:46:51.410
She's got her kid.

00:46:51.410 --> 00:46:52.710
You know and by the, you get to
the end of it and you're going,

00:46:52.710 --> 00:46:54.010
you're in the middle
of a bank robbery.

00:46:54.010 --> 00:46:59.210
And the way he could just sort
of slip you from the banal

00:46:59.210 --> 00:47:00.760
into the very, very violent.

00:47:00.760 --> 00:47:02.160
And put you in situations
you kind

00:47:02.160 --> 00:47:03.990
of can't imagine that you're in.

00:47:03.990 --> 00:47:05.850
You know I think was the
wonderful thing he did

00:47:05.850 --> 00:47:07.150
in his work.

00:47:07.150 --> 00:47:08.450
And I aspire to do
it in my work.

00:47:08.450 --> 00:47:09.750
Particularly when you're
dealing with violence.

00:47:09.750 --> 00:47:11.050
Because the thing
we often forget

00:47:11.050 --> 00:47:13.170
about violence is it
is, it is so banal.

00:47:13.170 --> 00:47:15.300
&gt;&gt; Marie Arana: Right.

00:47:15.300 --> 00:47:18.880
The dealing with violence, it
seems to me you know, the, the,

00:47:18.880 --> 00:47:23.530
the, the, it's so physical.

00:47:23.530 --> 00:47:26.930
It's so concrete and it's,
it's, it's all around you.

00:47:26.930 --> 00:47:30.230
And yet and you deal with
these war situations.

00:47:30.230 --> 00:47:33.410
But you also said at
one point, Elliot, you,

00:47:33.410 --> 00:47:36.800
you quote actually
quote Faulkner.

00:47:36.800 --> 00:47:38.770
In which you say
the only, he said,

00:47:38.770 --> 00:47:42.300
"The only thing worth writing
about is the human heart

00:47:42.300 --> 00:47:44.540
in conflict with itself."

00:47:44.540 --> 00:47:46.110
That being the conflict.

00:47:46.110 --> 00:47:49.100
Not being the conflict
that's around you concretely.

00:47:49.100 --> 00:47:52.440
And, and possibly
threatening your life.

00:47:52.440 --> 00:47:56.140
It seems what interests you
more is the internal conflict

00:47:56.140 --> 00:47:57.440
that is going on.

00:47:57.440 --> 00:47:59.280
Even as that conflict
is happening.

00:47:59.280 --> 00:48:00.720
&gt;&gt; Elliot Ackerman: Well,
I think it's a [inaudible]

00:48:00.720 --> 00:48:02.340
that interests most people.

00:48:02.340 --> 00:48:04.290
I mean, characters
are interesting.

00:48:04.290 --> 00:48:05.890
It's, you know, it's
once you start getting

00:48:05.890 --> 00:48:07.190
into you know you
were talking before

00:48:07.190 --> 00:48:08.490
about you know what
does fiction do?

00:48:08.490 --> 00:48:09.790
You know, fiction takes you

00:48:09.790 --> 00:48:11.090
into the internal
lives of these people.

00:48:11.090 --> 00:48:13.080
And I think that's, that's
where you know that's

00:48:13.080 --> 00:48:14.480
where the most compelling
stories arise.

00:48:14.480 --> 00:48:17.900
You know and that's where
the, the emotion exists.

00:48:17.900 --> 00:48:21.580
And you know why write fiction
I think you know if you are able

00:48:21.580 --> 00:48:23.640
to make someone feel something.

00:48:23.640 --> 00:48:25.250
You know there'll
remember what they felt.

00:48:25.250 --> 00:48:27.300
In a way they might not
remember what they read

00:48:27.300 --> 00:48:31.000
in the paper that morning.

00:48:31.000 --> 00:48:32.500
&gt;&gt; Marie Arana: One
last question for you.

00:48:32.500 --> 00:48:34.980
And that is, you're a warrior.

00:48:34.980 --> 00:48:38.510
&gt;&gt; Elliot Ackerman:
On my good days.

00:48:38.510 --> 00:48:41.180
[ Laughter ]

00:48:41.180 --> 00:48:47.260
Marie Arana: You know, warriors
come home and things happen.

00:48:47.260 --> 00:48:53.060
And do, do we and I'm, I'm
trying to take this out to,

00:48:53.060 --> 00:49:03.660
to a, a more social or
political question, if you will.

00:49:03.660 --> 00:49:08.480
Why do we revere warriors?

00:49:08.480 --> 00:49:10.870
I mean, we revere
warriors from afar.

00:49:10.870 --> 00:49:13.990
When they come home, when they
are riddled with problems.

00:49:13.990 --> 00:49:19.200
When you know they may be
addicted to drugs or, or,

00:49:19.200 --> 00:49:21.890
or beating their
wives or you know,

00:49:21.890 --> 00:49:23.870
a female beating her husbands.

00:49:23.870 --> 00:49:26.000
Or not being good
to the children.

00:49:26.000 --> 00:49:29.290
How, why is it that
we're not so good

00:49:29.290 --> 00:49:32.800
at confronting those
issues that they bring home?

00:49:32.800 --> 00:49:34.100
&gt;&gt; Elliot Ackerman: Well,

00:49:34.100 --> 00:49:37.700
I think in some respects it's
easy you know at that point

00:49:37.700 --> 00:49:40.000
to look at them as the other.

00:49:40.000 --> 00:49:43.060
You know I've often,
probably most people

00:49:43.060 --> 00:49:45.830
who have my background
have, have the experience

00:49:45.830 --> 00:49:47.130
of you know someone
saying to them.

00:49:47.130 --> 00:49:49.800
Like you know I could never
imagine what you went through.

00:49:49.800 --> 00:49:51.350
I'm like, yeah you can.

00:49:51.350 --> 00:49:52.650
Sure you can.

00:49:52.650 --> 00:49:53.950
Like you know, you
can, maybe you've

00:49:53.950 --> 00:49:55.340
like passed by a car accident.

00:49:55.340 --> 00:49:57.540
Or you know you've lost
someone in your own family.

00:49:57.540 --> 00:49:58.850
But I think at the same time

00:49:58.850 --> 00:50:01.300
like saying I can never
imagine what you went through.

00:50:01.300 --> 00:50:03.220
Like always is unsettled to me.

00:50:03.220 --> 00:50:05.420
Not only because it kind
of shows, like you know,

00:50:05.420 --> 00:50:07.540
because it, because
it's, puts up some

00:50:07.540 --> 00:50:10.470
like lack of you know empathy.

00:50:10.470 --> 00:50:12.840
It's like if you can never
imagine what I went through,

00:50:12.840 --> 00:50:14.500
or what someone went
through in this.

00:50:14.500 --> 00:50:16.800
Then what you're basically
saying is that like I have been

00:50:16.800 --> 00:50:20.220
so inalterably changed or one
has been so inalterably changed

00:50:20.220 --> 00:50:24.960
by an experience that you can
no longer identify with them.

00:50:24.960 --> 00:50:26.340
So if you can't understand
what I went through.

00:50:26.340 --> 00:50:27.940
It means I have been
so unalterably changed

00:50:27.940 --> 00:50:29.240
that I can never go back

00:50:29.240 --> 00:50:31.350
to being the person
I was before I left.

00:50:31.350 --> 00:50:34.270
If I can never go back to being
the person I was before I left,

00:50:34.270 --> 00:50:38.290
it in effect means I
can never come home.

00:50:38.290 --> 00:50:40.900
And that's, you know,
and that's, that's,

00:50:40.900 --> 00:50:43.120
that's somewhere we,
we just can't be.

00:50:43.120 --> 00:50:46.880
So, so I think that you know
that, that maybe the answer

00:50:46.880 --> 00:50:50.320
to your question is you know
just a general lack of empathy.

00:50:50.320 --> 00:50:51.620
And lack of being able

00:50:51.620 --> 00:50:53.700
to you know see ourselves
collectively you know

00:50:53.700 --> 00:50:55.780
in these wars.

00:50:55.780 --> 00:50:57.080
&gt;&gt; Marie Arana: Right, right.

00:50:57.080 --> 00:51:02.860
And with that, I want to
bring on Sam Quinones,

00:51:02.860 --> 00:51:06.510
who deals with issues of-- .

00:51:06.510 --> 00:51:13.170
[ Applause ]

00:51:13.170 --> 00:51:15.140
And, and here's what I
want to read about Sam.

00:51:15.140 --> 00:51:18.460
This was written by, by
Laura Miller at Slate.

00:51:18.460 --> 00:51:21.410
"Many nonfiction books are
padded magazine features.

00:51:21.410 --> 00:51:23.730
But Dreamland, the
three-pronged story

00:51:23.730 --> 00:51:26.880
of how heroin addiction
become, became epidemic

00:51:26.880 --> 00:51:28.540
in small town America.

00:51:28.540 --> 00:51:30.620
Is the book Quinones
has to quit his job

00:51:30.620 --> 00:51:32.390
at the L.A. Times to write.

00:51:32.390 --> 00:51:34.840
You won't find this story
better told anywhere else.

00:51:34.840 --> 00:51:37.700
From the economic hollowing-out
of the middle class.

00:51:37.700 --> 00:51:39.380
To the greedy, reckless
marketing

00:51:39.380 --> 00:51:40.860
of pharmaceutical opiates

00:51:40.860 --> 00:51:43.760
to the remarkable
entrepreneurial industry

00:51:43.760 --> 00:51:47.830
of the residents of the obscure
Mexican state of Nayarit.

00:51:47.830 --> 00:51:49.670
All of these factors combine

00:51:49.670 --> 00:51:52.100
to create an opiate-addicted
population

00:51:52.100 --> 00:51:55.380
in small American cities
like Portsmouth, Ohio.

00:51:55.380 --> 00:51:58.130
Where residents, priced
out of pill mills,

00:51:58.130 --> 00:52:01.670
turn to a new and
newly cheap high.

00:52:01.670 --> 00:52:04.210
Dreamland, true crime, sociology

00:52:04.210 --> 00:52:07.420
and expose illuminates a
catastrophe unfolding all

00:52:07.420 --> 00:52:10.430
around us, right now."

00:52:10.430 --> 00:52:12.880
Sam, you've covered the border.

00:52:12.880 --> 00:52:15.030
You've covered US-Mexico
relations.

00:52:15.030 --> 00:52:17.820
You've been a Latin
American correspondent for,

00:52:17.820 --> 00:52:19.120
for many, many years.

00:52:19.120 --> 00:52:26.500
At what point did the opioid
crisis get your attention?

00:52:26.500 --> 00:52:31.130
&gt;&gt; Sam Quinones: Well I, I
began a story about when I was

00:52:31.130 --> 00:52:35.890
at the L.A. Times about
a small town in Mexico.

00:52:35.890 --> 00:52:38.740
Where everybody comes
to the United States

00:52:38.740 --> 00:52:41.670
to sell heroin like pizza.

00:52:41.670 --> 00:52:44.580
So there's a delivery system
where you call a number

00:52:44.580 --> 00:52:47.790
and then you have the
operator takes your order

00:52:47.790 --> 00:52:49.200
and then dispatches someone.

00:52:49.200 --> 00:52:51.460
To, to meet you when-- it's a,

00:52:51.460 --> 00:52:54.310
it's basically Domino's
Pizza of heroin.

00:52:54.310 --> 00:52:59.430
I came upon it when I was
talking a guy with the DEA

00:52:59.430 --> 00:53:04.040
in Columbus who said, "You know,
we've got this system here.

00:53:04.040 --> 00:53:05.340
We've got these guys doing this.

00:53:05.340 --> 00:53:06.910
We've never seen this before.

00:53:06.910 --> 00:53:10.590
No guns, they don't use guns.

00:53:10.590 --> 00:53:12.560
They're, they're, they're
and we can arrest them

00:53:12.560 --> 00:53:13.860
and arrest them and arrest them.

00:53:13.860 --> 00:53:15.160
And they send out more people.

00:53:15.160 --> 00:53:17.560
They reconstitute like
a, like a some kind

00:53:17.560 --> 00:53:20.640
of a mutant, very quickly."

00:53:20.640 --> 00:53:25.480
And he said, "They're
all from the same town."

00:53:25.480 --> 00:53:29.580
And that, I had written, I had
lived in Mexico for ten years.

00:53:29.580 --> 00:53:30.950
And I had written a lot

00:53:30.950 --> 00:53:33.760
about you see this
a lot across Mexico.

00:53:33.760 --> 00:53:35.830
Where towns have,
whereas one town,

00:53:35.830 --> 00:53:38.160
towns where people do one job.

00:53:38.160 --> 00:53:42.190
And, and there's one town in
my first book where everybody

00:53:42.190 --> 00:53:45.150
in the town makes popsicles.

00:53:45.150 --> 00:53:49.090
One of the great businesses,
businesses for arriving

00:53:49.090 --> 00:53:52.150
at the middle class in Mexico
is the popsicle business.

00:53:52.150 --> 00:53:53.450
And there's a business,

00:53:53.450 --> 00:53:55.560
if you know Mexico,
you know, Paleteria.

00:53:55.560 --> 00:53:57.080
That means [inaudible]
is everywhere.

00:53:57.080 --> 00:54:00.060
And that's one town
started that.

00:54:00.060 --> 00:54:04.240
And, and you go to the town,
and there's a, in the front

00:54:04.240 --> 00:54:08.530
of the town, there's a two-story
concrete popsicle statue.

00:54:08.530 --> 00:54:10.900
Saying thank you to the
popsicle for bringing them

00:54:10.900 --> 00:54:12.200
into the middle class.

00:54:12.200 --> 00:54:14.560
So when you told me that,
I knew he was right.

00:54:14.560 --> 00:54:15.920
I knew there had to
be a town out there.

00:54:15.920 --> 00:54:17.220
He didn't know which one.

00:54:17.220 --> 00:54:19.470
He said it was Tepic, Nayarit.

00:54:19.470 --> 00:54:20.770
I knew it was not Tepic.

00:54:20.770 --> 00:54:24.800
Tepic is a capital city, 350,000
people of the state of Nayarit.

00:54:24.800 --> 00:54:26.100
I knew that could not be true.

00:54:26.100 --> 00:54:27.400
It had to be a small town.

00:54:27.400 --> 00:54:30.330
So I began to write to
guys who had been arrested

00:54:30.330 --> 00:54:32.140
and were now in federal prison.

00:54:32.140 --> 00:54:35.720
And one after another, I wrote
20, 30 letters to these guys.

00:54:35.720 --> 00:54:39.430
Hey, do you want to talk about
your pizza heroin system?

00:54:39.430 --> 00:54:41.420
You know, basically
is what I did.

00:54:41.420 --> 00:54:44.100
And one guy, one guy
kind of got back to me.

00:54:44.100 --> 00:54:45.400
Says, yeah.

00:54:45.400 --> 00:54:47.990
We're not from Tepic, we're from
