01:18:44.910 --> 01:18:46.860
&gt;&gt; Jonathan Franzen: Sam, is it?

01:18:46.860 --> 01:18:50.230
Is it your impression
that the, that these are,

01:18:50.230 --> 01:18:52.340
you say it's about supply.

01:18:52.340 --> 01:18:54.660
That seems to imply these
are, these are people

01:18:54.660 --> 01:18:58.660
who if they hadn't happened
to have access to the opioids,

01:18:58.660 --> 01:19:02.900
they would have had good,
successful, satisfying lives?

01:19:02.900 --> 01:19:04.200
&gt;&gt; Sam Quinones:
It's hard to say.

01:19:04.200 --> 01:19:05.500
You're right.

01:19:05.500 --> 01:19:06.800
&gt;&gt; Jonathan Franzen:
Because that, I,

01:19:06.800 --> 01:19:09.130
the mention of Afghanistan
puts me at, and there is this,

01:19:09.130 --> 01:19:12.540
and as I said, there's this,
we were talking backstage.

01:19:12.540 --> 01:19:14.800
There is an overlap
between areas of,

01:19:14.800 --> 01:19:18.290
certainly where the opioid
crisis first made itself

01:19:18.290 --> 01:19:19.590
particularly visible.

01:19:19.590 --> 01:19:21.470
And Trump America.

01:19:21.470 --> 01:19:23.640
There is a, there is a
kind of despair and a sort

01:19:23.640 --> 01:19:26.450
of let's just burn
it all down quality.

01:19:26.450 --> 01:19:28.640
And that's absolutely
what happens if you tear

01:19:28.640 --> 01:19:30.820
up a country with
17 years of war.

01:19:30.820 --> 01:19:34.770
I mean, there's like,
why not keep fighting?

01:19:34.770 --> 01:19:37.230
&gt;&gt; But there's also the sense
in what you were talking about,

01:19:37.230 --> 01:19:38.570
too, which was this, you know,

01:19:38.570 --> 01:19:40.780
this fantasia that
we're living in.

01:19:40.780 --> 01:19:44.470
Oh yes, we can have you know
opioid drugs and be fine.

01:19:44.470 --> 01:19:47.210
It's also the sense
of you know, oh yeah,

01:19:47.210 --> 01:19:48.740
we can [inaudible]
our institutions

01:19:48.740 --> 01:19:50.410
and we'll all be
psychologically okay.

01:19:50.410 --> 01:19:53.420
Like oh yeah, we can just
you know resource our wars

01:19:53.420 --> 01:19:54.720
out to other people.

01:19:54.720 --> 01:19:56.020
And not pay taxes
on them, and yeah,

01:19:56.020 --> 01:19:57.320
that's going to work out fine.

01:19:57.320 --> 01:19:58.780
Like it's probably,
it was a good thing

01:19:58.780 --> 01:20:00.490
that we had a draft
in the sixties.

01:20:00.490 --> 01:20:03.220
You know. And then everybody
you know got to a certain point.

01:20:03.220 --> 01:20:05.010
It was like this makes no sense.

01:20:05.010 --> 01:20:06.310
We're not doing it anymore.

01:20:06.310 --> 01:20:08.330
And now, you just
don't [inaudible].

01:20:08.330 --> 01:20:09.630
&gt;&gt; Sam Quinones: Exactly.

01:20:09.630 --> 01:20:11.850
Oh, 100%. I've said
this, in fact, in my,

01:20:11.850 --> 01:20:14.900
in talks that I've been giving
around the country about this.

01:20:14.900 --> 01:20:18.780
That, that it's like we,
yeah, we just have this like.

01:20:18.780 --> 01:20:22.450
The whole, the whole
theme really is to me,

01:20:22.450 --> 01:20:25.650
I thought again it was drug
trafficking and that's not that.

01:20:25.650 --> 01:20:29.830
It's, it's isolation
versus community.

01:20:29.830 --> 01:20:33.220
You know we used to treat
pain in a variety of ways.

01:20:33.220 --> 01:20:35.660
One person would get a
variety of approaches.

01:20:35.660 --> 01:20:37.320
So it would be you have pain?

01:20:37.320 --> 01:20:38.620
Chronic pain?

01:20:38.620 --> 01:20:40.250
Well cognitive behavioral
therapy.

01:20:40.250 --> 01:20:41.550
Diet, swimming.

01:20:41.550 --> 01:20:43.370
Pain? Marital counseling,
you know?

01:20:43.370 --> 01:20:44.670
You need that.

01:20:44.670 --> 01:20:45.980
The, the marriage is pain.

01:20:45.980 --> 01:20:47.710
So [laughter] if you-- .

01:20:47.710 --> 01:20:50.040
Seriously, that's what
they would, that's why part

01:20:50.040 --> 01:20:54.560
of what went into, but then
we, the pills took up all the.

01:20:54.560 --> 01:20:57.270
We began to believe in easy
answers to complicated problems.

01:20:57.270 --> 01:21:00.840
We began to have a-- I told
an audience the other day.

01:21:00.840 --> 01:21:02.920
I can't remember
where it was now.

01:21:02.920 --> 01:21:06.210
That one of the worst things
we ever did was go to war.

01:21:06.210 --> 01:21:08.480
And then give us, give
ourselves a tax cut.

01:21:08.480 --> 01:21:11.540
It's like we didn't really,
there's one infinitesimal part

01:21:11.540 --> 01:21:13.950
of our population was going
ask to be going over there

01:21:13.950 --> 01:21:15.340
and risk their lives
to fight a war.

01:21:15.340 --> 01:21:18.370
And we were not supposed
to feel anything.

01:21:18.370 --> 01:21:20.200
We just all want it
to be narc at times.

01:21:20.200 --> 01:21:22.070
We all want it to
be kind of immune.

01:21:22.070 --> 01:21:24.010
And what's more and very,
very important in all

01:21:24.010 --> 01:21:25.550
of this I believe,
very important.

01:21:25.550 --> 01:21:28.610
Is that we, we were not
asked to be accountable.

01:21:28.610 --> 01:21:30.260
And not, with pain either.

01:21:30.260 --> 01:21:33.290
We were not asked to
say, you know, when you,

01:21:33.290 --> 01:21:34.770
you have chronic pains.

01:21:34.770 --> 01:21:36.070
Very often it has to do

01:21:36.070 --> 01:21:39.740
with your own personal
consumer decisions.

01:21:39.740 --> 01:21:41.070
You don't get enough exercise.

01:21:41.070 --> 01:21:42.370
You eat poorly, you smoke.

01:21:42.370 --> 01:21:43.670
You drink.

01:21:43.670 --> 01:21:44.970
You're on a variety of things.

01:21:44.970 --> 01:21:46.780
Doctors found the patients
didn't want to hear that.

01:21:46.780 --> 01:21:48.610
You know? And so they
just said, "You know,

01:21:48.610 --> 01:21:50.750
doc, I want you to fix me.

01:21:50.750 --> 01:21:52.050
You're the car mechanic.

01:21:52.050 --> 01:21:53.350
My body's a car.

01:21:53.350 --> 01:21:54.650
Fix me, you know?"

01:21:54.650 --> 01:21:56.810
And we got into this
attitude of,

01:21:56.810 --> 01:21:59.820
that I believe was
also very kind of,

01:21:59.820 --> 01:22:01.420
just a narcotized attitude.

01:22:01.420 --> 01:22:03.250
That we don't want
to have to deal

01:22:03.250 --> 01:22:06.100
with our own, our own decisions.

01:22:06.100 --> 01:22:10.290
We don't, or, or, or, or change
our way of, of, of living.

01:22:10.290 --> 01:22:13.300
And part of it is
when we went to war.

01:22:13.300 --> 01:22:17.940
And took, and, and were
happy to get a tax cut.

01:22:17.940 --> 01:22:20.650
I mean, one of the lowest
points in our culture,

01:22:20.650 --> 01:22:21.950
frankly was right there.

01:22:21.950 --> 01:22:25.530
Really it was a very
sad day, I thought.

01:22:27.250 --> 01:22:28.550
&gt;&gt; Marie Arana: Before we move

01:22:28.550 --> 01:22:30.990
on to the last segment
of this program.

01:22:30.990 --> 01:22:34.040
I want to thank these
extraordinary writers

01:22:34.040 --> 01:22:41.150
who in one way or another speak
to I think Denis Johnson's work.

01:22:41.150 --> 01:22:49.950
His sort of miraculous
ability to take so many themes

01:22:49.950 --> 01:22:51.550
that we've talked about here.

01:22:51.550 --> 01:22:57.180
And merge them into express--
the spectacular literature.

01:22:57.180 --> 01:22:59.210
So thank you to Jonathan
Franzen,

01:22:59.210 --> 01:23:03.650
thank you to Elliot Ackerman,
thank you to Sam Quinones,

01:23:03.650 --> 01:23:07.310
before we move onto the
next part of the program.

01:23:07.310 --> 01:23:08.790
The very tail end.

01:23:08.790 --> 01:23:11.510
Thank you so much.

01:23:11.510 --> 01:23:27.220
[ Applause ]

01:23:27.220 --> 01:23:34.220
And now, to, to tell us about
the personal, more personal side

01:23:34.220 --> 01:23:38.790
of Denis Johnson, I want to
welcome Elizabeth Cuthrell

01:23:38.790 --> 01:23:41.930
to come and talk about
her personal recollections

01:23:41.930 --> 01:23:45.460
and her work in film with Denis.

01:23:45.460 --> 01:23:47.260
Elizabeth, please.

01:23:47.260 --> 01:23:56.040
[ Applause ]

01:23:56.040 --> 01:23:57.340
&gt;&gt; Elizabeth: Good
evening everybody.

01:23:57.340 --> 01:23:59.400
Thank you for being here.

01:23:59.400 --> 01:24:02.400
I think I'm going to
usher in a different tone.

01:24:02.400 --> 01:24:04.050
I hope that's okay.

01:24:04.050 --> 01:24:09.220
I first met Denis in
1997 when my partners

01:24:09.220 --> 01:24:12.810
and I were writing the
screenplay for Jesus' Son.

01:24:12.810 --> 01:24:14.980
We were just starting
out in the film business.

01:24:14.980 --> 01:24:17.190
It was our first project.

01:24:17.190 --> 01:24:20.430
I was a huge fan of Denis' work.

01:24:20.430 --> 01:24:22.830
I had somehow convinced
him in a phone call

01:24:22.830 --> 01:24:25.730
to let us take a
whack at the script.

01:24:25.730 --> 01:24:29.450
I promised him if he hated it,
we wouldn't make the movie.

01:24:29.450 --> 01:24:31.430
And he knew I meant it.

01:24:31.430 --> 01:24:33.040
We sent him the first draft.

01:24:33.040 --> 01:24:37.430
He loved it, and asked to come
to New York City to meet us.

01:24:37.430 --> 01:24:41.800
He ambled into the meting
wearing a vintage Aloha shirt.

01:24:41.800 --> 01:24:46.870
Red cowboy boots, and Elvis
Presley glasses held together

01:24:46.870 --> 01:24:49.020
in the middle by tape.

01:24:49.020 --> 01:24:51.280
I was terrified and thrilled

01:24:51.280 --> 01:24:54.400
to meet this genius whose
book we were adapting.

01:24:54.400 --> 01:24:58.030
He seemed shy and
amused at the same time.

01:24:58.030 --> 01:25:01.190
But what I remember
most was his generosity.

01:25:01.190 --> 01:25:04.660
He marveled at our
adaptation and talked to us

01:25:04.660 --> 01:25:09.540
like we were the geniuses and he
was the kid just starting out.

01:25:09.540 --> 01:25:12.360
I asked him if he'd be willing
to play a part in the film.

01:25:12.360 --> 01:25:15.690
And he said, "Only if I
can play Terrance Weber,

01:25:15.690 --> 01:25:18.220
the guy with the
knife in his eye."

01:25:19.510 --> 01:25:22.100
[Laughter] He added, "That
way, if I hate the movie,

01:25:22.100 --> 01:25:24.530
I can use my performance
as a metaphor."

01:25:24.530 --> 01:25:25.830
[Laughter]

01:25:25.830 --> 01:25:29.600
So a year later, we were
on the film set together.

01:25:29.600 --> 01:25:30.950
Denis was effusive.

01:25:30.950 --> 01:25:33.470
He kept saying, "This is
exactly what it looked like.

01:25:33.470 --> 01:25:36.160
This is exactly what
it felt like."

01:25:36.160 --> 01:25:38.810
In the clip we're about
to show you, Jack Black

01:25:38.810 --> 01:25:42.560
and Billy Crudup are working
in the ER of a hospital.

01:25:42.560 --> 01:25:44.330
They've raided the
medicine cabinet.

01:25:44.330 --> 01:25:47.340
And they are hammered
on a, just a cocktail

01:25:47.340 --> 01:25:49.320
of uppers and downers.

01:25:49.320 --> 01:25:53.780
When a guy named Terrance Weber,
played by Denis Johnson arrives.

01:25:53.780 --> 01:25:56.080
Here's the clip.

01:26:02.100 --> 01:26:05.020
&gt;&gt; I'd been working
in the emergency ward

01:26:05.020 --> 01:26:06.980
for about three weeks, I guess.

01:26:06.980 --> 01:26:09.650
I'd taken the job because
Michelle was pregnant

01:26:09.650 --> 01:26:12.300
and I was trying
to be responsible.

01:26:12.300 --> 01:26:13.740
I had nothing to do on
the overnight shift,

01:26:13.740 --> 01:26:15.370
so I went looking for Georgie.

01:26:15.370 --> 01:26:16.720
The orderly.

01:26:16.720 --> 01:26:18.800
He often stole pills
from the cabinet.

01:26:18.800 --> 01:26:21.510
&gt;&gt; What am I going to do about
these fucking shoes, man?

01:26:21.510 --> 01:26:31.440
[ Music ]

01:26:31.440 --> 01:26:33.610
&gt;&gt; Whatever you stole, I guess
you ate it already, right?

01:26:33.610 --> 01:26:38.510
&gt;&gt; Listen to how they squish!

01:26:38.510 --> 01:26:46.220
[ Music ]

01:26:46.220 --> 01:26:48.510
&gt;&gt; Let me just check
your pockets, okay?

01:26:48.510 --> 01:26:53.080
[ Music ]

01:26:53.080 --> 01:26:55.750
Yeah. No. Oh.

01:27:00.780 --> 01:27:02.580
Oh, yeah. Here's something.

01:27:02.580 --> 01:27:09.510
[ Music ]

01:27:09.510 --> 01:27:30.040
[ Chuckles to Himself ]

01:27:30.040 --> 01:27:31.980
&gt;&gt; I hope you didn't
do this to him!

01:27:31.980 --> 01:27:33.280
&gt;&gt; Me? No.

01:27:33.280 --> 01:27:36.310
He was like this.

01:27:36.310 --> 01:27:39.570
&gt;&gt; My wife did it.

01:27:39.570 --> 01:27:42.180
&gt;&gt; Who brought you in?

01:27:42.180 --> 01:27:43.480
&gt;&gt; Nobody.

01:27:43.480 --> 01:27:45.360
I just walked down.

01:27:45.360 --> 01:27:48.600
It's only three blocks.

01:27:49.620 --> 01:27:51.740
&gt;&gt; Oh, we, we'd better
get you lying down.

01:27:51.740 --> 01:27:55.560
&gt;&gt; Okay, I feel ready
for something like that.

01:28:01.110 --> 01:28:02.410
&gt;&gt; Name.

01:28:02.410 --> 01:28:03.710
&gt;&gt; Terrance Weber.

01:28:03.710 --> 01:28:05.590
&gt;&gt; Your face is dark, I
can't see what you're saying.

01:28:05.590 --> 01:28:06.890
&gt;&gt; Georgie?

01:28:06.890 --> 01:28:08.190
&gt;&gt; What are you saying man?

01:28:08.190 --> 01:28:09.490
I can't see.

01:28:09.490 --> 01:28:10.790
&gt;&gt; What's going on, Georgie.

01:28:10.790 --> 01:28:12.090
&gt;&gt; His face is dark.

01:28:12.090 --> 01:28:13.390
&gt;&gt; How long ago did this happen?

01:28:13.390 --> 01:28:14.690
&gt;&gt; Just a while ago.

01:28:14.690 --> 01:28:15.990
My wife did it.

01:28:15.990 --> 01:28:18.730
I was peeping on the lady next
door while she was bathing.

01:28:19.810 --> 01:28:21.460
My wife waited until
I'd fell asleep

01:28:21.460 --> 01:28:24.500
and then she decided
she's blind me.

01:28:24.500 --> 01:28:27.440
&gt;&gt; Do you want me
to call the police?

01:28:31.040 --> 01:28:33.740
&gt;&gt; Not unless I die.

01:28:33.740 --> 01:28:35.770
&gt;&gt; Here's the situation.

01:28:35.770 --> 01:28:38.140
We, we need to get a team here.

01:28:38.140 --> 01:28:39.760
An entire team.

01:28:39.760 --> 01:28:42.200
I want a good eye man.

01:28:42.200 --> 01:28:43.740
The best eye man.

01:28:43.740 --> 01:28:45.350
A great eye man.

01:28:45.350 --> 01:28:47.250
I want brain surgeon.

01:28:47.250 --> 01:28:49.340
And I want a really
good gas man.

01:28:49.340 --> 01:28:50.640
Get me a genius.

01:28:50.640 --> 01:28:52.430
I'm not touching that head.

01:28:52.430 --> 01:28:53.730
We'll, we'll prep this guy.

01:28:53.730 --> 01:28:55.270
And we'll just sit back
and just sit tight.

01:28:55.270 --> 01:28:57.570
&gt;&gt; Alright.

01:29:01.660 --> 01:29:02.960
&gt;&gt; Orderly.

01:29:02.960 --> 01:29:05.290
Orderly.

01:29:05.290 --> 01:29:07.250
&gt;&gt; Do you mean me?

01:29:07.250 --> 01:29:09.010
Should I get him prepped?

01:29:09.010 --> 01:29:10.700
&gt;&gt; Is this a hospital?

01:29:10.700 --> 01:29:13.540
Is this the emergency room?

01:29:13.540 --> 01:29:14.840
Is that the patient?

01:29:14.840 --> 01:29:17.140
Are you the orderly?

01:29:19.690 --> 01:29:21.490
&gt;&gt; Oh, hey!

01:29:21.490 --> 01:29:26.110
[ Applause ]

01:29:26.110 --> 01:29:27.410
&gt;&gt; Elizabeth Cuthrell:
Thank you.

01:29:27.410 --> 01:29:30.410
Collaborating with
Denis on his stuff was

01:29:30.410 --> 01:29:32.480
like stepping into
another world.

01:29:32.480 --> 01:29:37.050
Something in me would always get
rearranged, open, challenged.

01:29:37.050 --> 01:29:39.880
We worked on a bunch of projects
together over the years.

01:29:39.880 --> 01:29:44.000
And were cooking up some new
ideas right up until the end.

01:29:44.000 --> 01:29:46.960
Denis was fierce about
protecting his work.

01:29:46.960 --> 01:29:49.060
If someone tried
to change or cut

01:29:49.060 --> 01:29:52.610
or wrongly interpret his
writing, he would be crushed.

01:29:52.610 --> 01:29:54.890
But he would also do what
he had to do to protect it.

01:29:54.890 --> 01:29:58.280
At a production of one
of his plays in Chicago,

01:29:58.280 --> 01:30:00.560
he arrived for the
final dress rehearsal

01:30:00.560 --> 01:30:01.910
and was stunned to realize.

01:30:01.910 --> 01:30:05.740
The director decided to use
this kind of sound machine

01:30:05.740 --> 01:30:07.040
to weave a creepy,

01:30:07.040 --> 01:30:10.110
weird background sound
into the production.

01:30:10.110 --> 01:30:11.940
Denis hated it.

01:30:11.940 --> 01:30:13.770
He spoke to the director
and producer,

01:30:13.770 --> 01:30:15.770
but they wouldn't budge.

01:30:15.770 --> 01:30:18.190
So as a last desperate measure,

01:30:18.190 --> 01:30:20.440
that night after
everyone had left.

01:30:20.440 --> 01:30:23.430
He snuck back into the theater.

01:30:23.430 --> 01:30:26.120
Stuck the sound machine
under his jacket.

01:30:26.120 --> 01:30:28.510
Went out and pitched
it into the river.

01:30:28.510 --> 01:30:31.040
[ Laughter ]

01:30:31.040 --> 01:30:34.220
Needless to say, he was locked
out of the theater from then on.

01:30:34.220 --> 01:30:38.310
In his writing, Denis
could be merciless.

01:30:38.310 --> 01:30:41.830
But as a friend, he
was profoundly kind.

01:30:41.830 --> 01:30:43.880
He saw into you, but
he didn't judge you.

01:30:43.880 --> 01:30:45.580
And when you made a bad choice,

01:30:45.580 --> 01:30:48.850
he'd help you find
something heroic about it.

01:30:48.850 --> 01:30:52.080
He was awake and aware,
and in my opinion hooked

01:30:52.080 --> 01:30:54.460
up to some sacred line.

01:30:54.460 --> 01:30:56.110
There were no layers on him.

01:30:56.110 --> 01:30:57.490
He felt everything.

01:30:57.490 --> 01:31:00.490
Ever infirmity, in detail,
and at the speed of light.

01:31:00.490 --> 01:31:03.100
And that can't be easy.

01:31:03.100 --> 01:31:06.230
But whenever I asked him how
he was, he would always say,

01:31:06.230 --> 01:31:09.510
"I'm getting better
and better every day."

01:31:09.510 --> 01:31:13.080
And in one of our very last
email exchanges, he wrote,

01:31:13.080 --> 01:31:15.520
"I thought late life was
supposed to be boring.

01:31:15.520 --> 01:31:20.660
I'm finding it more like a
trip over Niagara Falls."

01:31:20.660 --> 01:31:23.460
He sometimes sent me emails
that read like prayers.

01:31:23.460 --> 01:31:25.260
Here's one.

01:31:25.260 --> 01:31:27.520
"Elizabeth, my darling sister.

01:31:27.520 --> 01:31:31.070
The other night I was up for a
couple of hours around 2:00 AM.

01:31:31.070 --> 01:31:33.140
I call it the night watch.

01:31:33.140 --> 01:31:36.050
Sometimes it's the
best part of the day.

01:31:36.050 --> 01:31:39.680
I had an insight that I
wish I could have held onto.

01:31:39.680 --> 01:31:43.880
That everything is renewed,
replenished perpetually.

01:31:43.880 --> 01:31:47.260
And that's what we
are, that replenishing.

01:31:47.260 --> 01:31:49.510
I'm not the one being renewed.

01:31:49.510 --> 01:31:51.770
I'm the renewing itself.

01:31:51.770 --> 01:31:53.660
I'm not the one being healed.

01:31:53.660 --> 01:31:55.820
I'm the process of healing.

01:31:55.820 --> 01:31:57.720
That's the true me.

01:31:57.720 --> 01:32:00.240
I felt it was truth vividly.

01:32:00.240 --> 01:32:02.580
I was living it for
a little while.

01:32:02.580 --> 01:32:04.780
Now it's just a concept again.

01:32:04.780 --> 01:32:06.210
But a sweet one.

01:32:06.210 --> 01:32:10.280
And here I pass it on to you."

01:32:10.280 --> 01:32:14.150
Denis' openness and sensitivity
sometimes made it hard for him

01:32:14.150 --> 01:32:15.470
to deal with the rest of us.

01:32:15.470 --> 01:32:18.610
And especially the crazy
business side of art.

01:32:18.610 --> 01:32:20.240
He told me when he
was out in L.A.,

01:32:20.240 --> 01:32:23.600
trying to get work made not long
after Tree of Smoke came out.

01:32:23.600 --> 01:32:27.170
How he got a kick out of all the
insane Hollywood bullshitters

01:32:27.170 --> 01:32:28.470
who would forget his name.

01:32:28.470 --> 01:32:32.980
But proudly introduce him
to each other as Dave.

01:32:32.980 --> 01:32:34.850
[Laughter] And say,
"This is Dave.

01:32:34.850 --> 01:32:36.830
He won the National Book Award."

01:32:36.830 --> 01:32:41.210
These kinds of experiences
encouraged him to treat,

01:32:41.210 --> 01:32:43.530
retreat back to Idaho or Arizona

01:32:43.530 --> 01:32:46.680
and earn his reputation
as being reclusive.

01:32:46.680 --> 01:32:49.690
But there was something about
the process of making plays,

01:32:49.690 --> 01:32:52.830
screenplays and teleplays that
brought out a part of Denis

01:32:52.830 --> 01:32:56.260
that was jazzed and
collaborative and social.

01:32:56.260 --> 01:32:57.800
And he couldn't stay away from.

01:32:57.800 --> 01:33:00.300
And he loved actors.

01:33:00.300 --> 01:33:03.300
He would sometimes go into
ecstatic states listen

01:33:03.300 --> 01:33:05.440
to them make sense of his work.

01:33:05.440 --> 01:33:08.540
Here's part of an email he
wrote after a rehearsal.

01:33:08.540 --> 01:33:10.980
"Elizabeth, what a
privilege to sit in a room

01:33:10.980 --> 01:33:13.250
and watch these geniuses
at work.

01:33:13.250 --> 01:33:16.090
Afterwards, they talk
about their dinner plans.

01:33:16.090 --> 01:33:18.480
Head for an hour's subway ride.

01:33:18.480 --> 01:33:23.550
Go on as if it's possible to go
after an experience like that.

01:33:23.550 --> 01:33:26.780
I go back to the
apartment, ten minute walk.

01:33:26.780 --> 01:33:30.660
And try not to dissolve
into the galaxies."

01:33:32.290 --> 01:33:34.970
Lastly, I want to
talk just for a moment

01:33:34.970 --> 01:33:37.960
about Denis' wife,
Cindy Lee Johnson.

01:33:37.960 --> 01:33:40.870
Because there's really
no talking about Denis

01:33:40.870 --> 01:33:43.000
without talking about Cindy.

01:33:43.000 --> 01:33:44.300
She was his beloved.

01:33:44.300 --> 01:33:47.660
And when he spoke about
her and their kids.

01:33:47.660 --> 01:33:50.610
Their beautiful daughter
Lana, who's here tonight.

01:33:50.610 --> 01:33:54.020
It was truly like he
was channeling sunlight.

01:33:54.020 --> 01:33:57.120
Cindy took care of
everything the world demanded

01:33:57.120 --> 01:33:59.650
of Denis so he could make art.

01:33:59.650 --> 01:34:01.520
She was his buoy.

01:34:01.520 --> 01:34:03.290
Denis could be impulsive
with money.

01:34:03.290 --> 01:34:05.760
And he told me that once
Cindy took over the checkbook,

01:34:05.760 --> 01:34:09.430
the repo man stopped
coming for his car.

01:34:09.430 --> 01:34:11.470
[Laughter] He's always say,
"I don't know how she does it!

01:34:11.470 --> 01:34:13.020
Does she clip coupons?

01:34:13.020 --> 01:34:15.790
Buy everything at a fire sale?"

01:34:15.790 --> 01:34:17.700
She dazzled him.

01:34:17.700 --> 01:34:21.870
He never seemed to get over how
her love transformed his life.

01:34:21.870 --> 01:34:25.740
Denis would say things like,
"When Cindy goes somewhere even

01:34:25.740 --> 01:34:31.030
for a short while, it's
like God has died."

01:34:31.030 --> 01:34:34.320
This is my last story.

01:34:34.320 --> 01:34:37.200
I remember one afternoon
when Denis was giving a talk

01:34:37.200 --> 01:34:39.110
at the News School
in New York City.

01:34:39.110 --> 01:34:40.490
It was a rare appearance,

01:34:40.490 --> 01:34:42.680
totally sold out,
standing room only.

01:34:42.680 --> 01:34:45.030
It was raining, and
he got there late.

01:34:45.030 --> 01:34:47.650
Someone appeared and rushed
him through a side door

01:34:47.650 --> 01:34:48.990
and up onto the stage.

01:34:48.990 --> 01:34:51.700
And he got separated from Cindy.

01:34:51.700 --> 01:34:53.780
Another writer was
introducing him and going

01:34:53.780 --> 01:34:55.640
on a bit long with accolades.

01:34:55.640 --> 01:34:58.270
And I noticed Denis on
stage looking agitated.

01:34:58.270 --> 01:35:02.520
When he finally got to the mic,
he put his hand to his forehead

01:35:02.520 --> 01:35:04.190
to shade the bright light.

01:35:04.190 --> 01:35:07.570
And the first thing he
said was, "Cindy Lee?

01:35:07.570 --> 01:35:10.720
Honey? Where are you?"

01:35:10.720 --> 01:35:13.560
And she raised her arm and
called back, "I'm here."

01:35:13.560 --> 01:35:16.910
And he smiled his
incredible boyish smile

01:35:16.910 --> 01:35:18.310
at the sound of her voice.

01:35:18.310 --> 01:35:20.130
And he said, "I can't see you.

01:35:20.130 --> 01:35:21.940
Is your seat okay?

01:35:21.940 --> 01:35:23.240
Where are you?

01:35:23.240 --> 01:35:24.870
Can you stand up?"

01:35:24.870 --> 01:35:28.950
And she stood up and
said, "Yes, I'm okay.

01:35:28.950 --> 01:35:30.250
I'm here."

01:35:30.250 --> 01:35:33.580
And they smiled at
each other and flirted.

01:35:33.580 --> 01:35:36.360
And he said, "Alright then."

01:35:36.360 --> 01:35:39.210
And began to read a story.

01:35:39.210 --> 01:35:40.930
Alright then.

01:35:40.930 --> 01:35:43.080
It is my great honor

01:35:43.080 --> 01:35:47.510
to introduce my precious
friend, Cindy Lee Johnson.

01:35:47.510 --> 01:36:09.400
[ Applause ]

01:36:09.400 --> 01:36:10.700
&gt;&gt; Cindy Lee Johnson:
Good evening.

01:36:10.700 --> 01:36:12.000
Thank you, Elizabeth.

01:36:12.000 --> 01:36:13.300
Thank you to all
the panel members.

01:36:13.300 --> 01:36:16.120
What a wonderfully
unusual tribute.

01:36:16.120 --> 01:36:17.900
I love it.

01:36:17.900 --> 01:36:20.290
I also want to thank all
the ladies and gentlemen

01:36:20.290 --> 01:36:22.060
of the Library of Congress.

01:36:22.060 --> 01:36:24.380
For bestowing the esteemed Prize

01:36:24.380 --> 01:36:28.200
for American Fiction
upon my beloved husband.

01:36:28.200 --> 01:36:31.590
He so richly deserves it.

01:36:31.590 --> 01:36:35.160
When I met Denis,
he was 39 years old.

01:36:35.160 --> 01:36:36.830
And I immediately recognized him

01:36:36.830 --> 01:36:39.830
as the best-looking
man in the world.

01:36:39.830 --> 01:36:42.490
I fell in love straight away.

01:36:42.490 --> 01:36:44.870
Only later did I realize
he was the best writer

01:36:44.870 --> 01:36:48.110
in the world, in
my humble opinion.

01:36:48.110 --> 01:36:52.080
But he was also this
brave pilgrim soul.

01:36:52.080 --> 01:36:54.050
Who traveled the planet.

01:36:54.050 --> 01:36:57.720
From searching for
pirates in the Sulu Sea.

01:36:57.720 --> 01:37:01.110
To being the last American in
Somalia when the UN withdrew.

01:37:01.110 --> 01:37:06.740
And consider this from a
letter he wrote in 1991.

01:37:06.740 --> 01:37:11.220
"Dear Astronaut Selection
Officer, I am a civilian

01:37:11.220 --> 01:37:12.520
who would like to be considered

01:37:12.520 --> 01:37:16.310
for the one-year
astronaut training program."

01:37:16.310 --> 01:37:20.630
That's right, he tried
to go into space!

01:37:20.630 --> 01:37:23.740
[Laughter] He was like
a modern day Tom Sawyer.

01:37:23.740 --> 01:37:26.690
Often he would embark
with just a fishing vest.

01:37:26.690 --> 01:37:29.920
Filled with everything he
imagined he might need.

01:37:29.920 --> 01:37:33.490
And the faith that he would
encounter helpers, teachers,

01:37:33.490 --> 01:37:36.590
and guides along his path.

01:37:36.590 --> 01:37:39.190
And he always did.

01:37:39.190 --> 01:37:42.590
His life was a grand adventure.

01:37:42.590 --> 01:37:44.570
He loved this world.

01:37:44.570 --> 01:37:46.880
He loved his family.

01:37:46.880 --> 01:37:48.880
And he loved his work.

01:37:48.880 --> 01:37:52.150
I'm so grateful to
have his work.

01:37:52.150 --> 01:37:55.450
His light shines
through in his writing,

01:37:55.450 --> 01:37:57.340
and it's a gift to the world.

01:37:57.340 --> 01:38:03.300
But oh, how I miss that man.

01:38:03.300 --> 01:38:05.380
I will always love him.

01:38:05.380 --> 01:38:10.730
And so to close, a slideshow.

01:38:10.730 --> 01:38:12.030
I believe it will bear

01:38:12.030 --> 01:38:16.530
out my best-looking man
in the world comment.

01:38:16.530 --> 01:38:20.800
[Laughter] Also, please keep an
eye out for that fishing vest.

01:38:20.800 --> 01:38:22.560
Thank you.

01:38:22.560 --> 01:38:25.510
[ Applause ]

